<HEAD>Socialist Mayor's Party Wins Mayoral Contest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, ``In about ...,'' to UPDATE number of towns
voting on death-penalty resolution.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four-term socialist Mayor <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>' party won another victory Tuesday, as former community development director <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> defeated <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chioffi </PERSON> to become <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>' successor <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> candidate, had 5,626 ballots, or 52 percent of the vote, to 4,400, or 41 percent, for Democrat <PERSON> Chioffi </PERSON>, a store owner who also had Republican backing, according to unofficial results. Sanders _ often billed as the nation's only socialist mayor _ had decided against another term. <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> shies away from the socialist label, but ran under the banner of <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>' party. `` Today was a referendum on Progressive government, and we won it,'' <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> told a throng of 150 supporters. He said he would continue to push most of <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>' platform, which includes affordable housing and public access to the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION> waterfront. Also in the race were Greens party candidate <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Baird </PERSON> and `` tax revolt'' candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hackett </PERSON>. <PERSON> Baird </PERSON> received 596 votes, or 5 percent, and <PERSON> Hackett </PERSON> 91, or slightly less than 1 percent. Cold weather, which brought the wind chill factor to 43 degrees below zero Tuesday morning, may have kept some of the city's 25,000 registered voters away from the ballot box. <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamarche </PERSON>, secretary to City Clerk <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rader </PERSON>, said turnout was below average in the city of 38,000. The Progressives' success once again deprives the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of the mayor's seat, which Democrats have not held since <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> beat longtime incumbent <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Paquette </PERSON> by 10 votes in 1981. <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> said the win was significant because it showed the Progressives' strength. `` It's not a one-man show, it's a movement,'' he said. `` That's what we've accomplished tonight. He said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> voters have been demoralized by the political process. `` People look to the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, they do n't see anything. They look to the Republicans, and they do n't see anything. There is one city in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that has said we can go beyond staus quo politics, we can talk real issues to the people, we can have a dream of a city and a state and county that is fundamentally different than it is now,'' <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> said. The 47-year-old mayor, who is known for railing against the rich and powerful, decided in the fall to leave politics to teach and write. With a promise to fight for the underdog, the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, native was elected in 1981 by 10 votes over a Democrat. He was re-elected three times by more comfortable margins, winning in 1987 with 6,901 votes to 5,594 votes. Even <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>' critics give him credit for reinvigorating city politics. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and World Report rated him in 1987 as one of the nation's 20 best mayors. <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> has prospered and has been ranked highly in national quality-of-life surveys. Elsewhere around <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> it was Town Meeting Day, and residents braved the cold to travel to their town halls and approve school budgets and socialize with friends and neighbors not seen for a year. In nearly 70 towns, residents voted on a non-binding resolution asking the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to reinstate the death penalty, last used in the 1950s. At least 45 towns supported capital punishment, but 18 rejected or tabled it. One town that voted down the resolution cited the recent film, `` The Thin Blue Line,'' which suggests that an innocent man faced the death penalty in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Two years ago, about 30 towns took up the question, and two-thirds voted for reinstatement, said Republican Rep. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheltra </PERSON>, a proponent of capital punishment and major force behind the town meeting resolution.
</TEXT>
