<HEAD>Some Charges Dismissed After Judge Blasts Prosecutors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Monday dismissed charges against half of the 14 defendants in a massive, mob-linked drug conspiracy trial, finding prosecutors failed to prove their case because of `` ineptitude.'' `` If these drug dealers are walking free it's because you people are not competent,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprizzo </PERSON> told protesting prosecutors as he dismissed narcotics conspiracy charges against seven defendants in the Pizza Connection II drug trial. `` You let them go,'' <PERSON> Sprizzo </PERSON> told prosecutors later in the day. `` Do n't lay at my feet your ineptitude.'' The judge then barred lawyers from talking to reporters about the case. <PERSON> Sprizzo </PERSON> dropped the drug conspiracy charge after the government finished presenting its case and defense lawyers, contending the charge was too broad, made routine requests for the dismissal of charges for lack of evidence. The trial, which began last October, is a spinoff from the original, 17-month-long Pizza Connection drug trial, so named because prosecutors accused the defendants of using pizzerias in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> as fronts for their heroin dealing and money-laundering conspiracy. Eighteen of the 19 defendants in the first Pizza Connection trial were convicted. The 14 defendants in the Pizza Connection II case were accused of participating in a massive conspiracy to distribute heroin, cocaine and marijuana. Some also were charged with possession of drugs with intent to distribute. The seven remaining defendants face maxiumum penalties of life in prison if convicted.
