to UPDATE with Jackson letter; picks up 13th graf, `` Jackson backed ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> fasted for three days because he hungers for the defeat of Democratic mayoral nominee <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, but some Democrats say <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s efforts are straining the two-time <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> presidential contender's party credentials. `` What kind of credibility does that give <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> nationwide with other Democrats?'' asks <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> party Chairman <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Demuzio </PERSON>. `` This is certainly not going to bode well for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> nationally if he has any future ambitions, which I'm sure he does.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> backed Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primary won last week by <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, but that was because his candidate of choice _ <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alderman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Timothy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> _ sat out the primary in favor of a third-party bid in the April 4 general election. The attack on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s party credentials is only the latest event in what has become an imbroglio in the politics of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s black community since <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, the city's first black mayor, died near the start of his second term in 1987 <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has tried to be a peacemaker, but his plea for unity among supporters of <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> during the primary went unheeded. Now his position is at odds with the man <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> successfully backed to head the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, the first black to hold the top post, has announced his support of <LOCATION> Daley </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. To top it off, Republicans have taken note of the black split in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and some see it as playing into the hands of new <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, who is trying to lure disenchanted blacks to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> says he is unfazed. `` In these contests, sometimes you win the votes and sometimes you do n't, but you must always preserve your dignity,'' he said Monday in a telephone interview while enroute from <LOCATION> Tuskegee </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION> `` What that <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> machine represents is a violation of people,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said of what he thinks would be a closed Democratic party under <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. `` It strips them of their dignity.'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> denies that he represents the past or the politics of his father, the late Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, who ran a vast patronage army. Young <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> talks, as do others, of unifying the city and giving all people opportunities. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> identifies the issue in his support of <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, running on the <ORGANIZATION> Harold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ticket, as `` reciprocity,'' meaning he wo n't support those who have n't supported him. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Russo </PERSON>, D-Ill., a <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> ally who has criticized <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s opposition to the Democratic mayoral nominee, received a letter from <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> that requested a meeting, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said later Monday `` If you are serious about unity in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, I am perfectly willing to meet with you and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> to discuss a similar deal,'' said the letter drafted by <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>. `` If I do run -LRB- for president -RRB- in 1992 will you support my candidacy as a favorite son? That is the basis of a reciprocal deal.'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the letter was `` kind of a rhetorical device.'' `` He's really not willing to talk to <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said. `` Rev. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is supporting <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> backed a slate of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> candidates last year, including <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> in his successful bid for a third term as county state's attorney. But he notes <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> did n't support him in his 1988 presidential bid and did n't endorse <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1987. `` I reached out to <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> and endorsed him, and yet he seems to have no sense of obligation to be reciprocal or fair,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> denies that race is the only issue, although <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> is white and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> is black. He says the issue is one of `` going forward'' instead of backwards. `` In <LOCATION> Daley </LOCATION>, there is relief for those who have a history of monopolizing; grief for those who've been locked out,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Saturday at an Operation PUSH meeting where he also announced his three-day fast. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who was taking only liquids, planned to return to a normal diet on Tuesday. A mostly white coalition of aldermen elected <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> over <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> a week after <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> died and many <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> supporters sat out last week's primary. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> got about half the votes <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> did from the city's 19 predominately black wards. Some political analysts say <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s run against the party's endorsed candidate in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> will have little bearing on his national standing `` It will certainly be used against him, but I think <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> politics is seen as.. a unique situation,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavanagh </PERSON> director of <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s Center for the <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said Monday `` People who like what he stands for probably wo n't care if he endorses the -LRB- Democratic mayoral -RRB- nominee or not.''
