<HEAD>Kennedy Says Time Ripe For Democrats To Seize Ideological Initiative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said Monday the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is `` succumbing to the delusion'' that the old ways will still work, opening the door for Democrats to regain the ideological initiative. `` It is time for Democrats to become once again the party of ideas,'' the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Democrat said in a lecture at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our opportunity now _ our responsibility _ is to ... to put forth a vision for the 1990s and beyond.'' The 1988 election, which he said was `` so apparently devoid of ideas,'' also revealed how important they are. The Republicans succeeded in defining the contest because `` there was no compelling Democratic message,'' he said. `` Competency was not enough,'' he said in a reference to the failed presidential campaign of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` Ideology, which is about ideas, was missing, and our opponents filled the gap ...'' `` If you do n't define yourself, your opponent will. That is very dangerous in life and devasting in politics,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said at a news conference after his speech. `` The Republicans were able to define both Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in a way I did n't recognize.'' The senator said the Democrats are now presented with a great opportunity because `` this <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> president _ and perhaps the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ have run out of ideas.'' `` The administraion has no agenda other than coping, no real budget, no major initiatives and very little to say about what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> calls ` the vision thing,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` The administration holds office, but does n't know what to do with it,'' he said. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> `` ca n't live permanently off the legacy of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> any more than Democrats can succeed by simply repeating <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> or <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. `` The other side is now succumbing to the delusion that did so much demage to Democrats in other days: They assume that old ways will continue to work, that they do n't have to rethink them, that they have won and will win if only they rerun the campaigns of the past.''
