<HEAD>Regulations Force Town's Only Laundry to Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents left high and dry when this town's only coin-operated laundry was forced to close over safety concerns now have to drive at least 15 miles to wash their clothes Others among the 50 or so Wash-Out customers travel 30 miles to do their laundry in other towns. `` I feel very badly if someone has to travel 32 miles to do a load of laundry,'' said <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> of the state Department of Natural Resources. `` On the other hand, I would feel a lot worse if someone contracted a disease that terminated their life.'' Authorities said <PERSON> Wash-Out </PERSON>'s owner, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, used to allow waste water into a sewer near a neighboring nursing home. But he was told last year the state agency would not renew its permit if the laundry continued to dump water there. `` They're going to have to change the law, because if they do n't, you're not going to see a Laundromat in a small town,'' said <PERSON> Morse </PERSON>, who closed his 13-year-old business recently.
