<SECOND>PM-China-US-Math,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Pupils Better Than Americans At Math</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese primary school pupils are far better at mathematics than <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> youngsters and are more organized and attentive in their studies, a study by experts from the two countries indicates. The study by the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> surveyed pupils in 20 <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> schools and 11 <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> schools, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported today. Professor <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ge </PERSON> of the Chinese academy's <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychology </ORGANIZATION> said in a report on the study that said one reason the Chinese outshined the Americans was that American textbooks teach less about fractions, ratios, proportion and decimals than Chinese textbooks. She also said Chinese teachers spend more time on math, and that general math concepts are taught earlier in Chinese than American schools. Ms. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> noted that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> children spend half their class time without leadership `` and are more likely to be engaged in inappropriate activities than Chinese students.'' American students spent less than half the time on assigned tasks as Chinese children, and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> children pay less attention to their teachers, the paper quoted her as saying. Ms. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> added that <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> children may be under greater social pressure to succeed because passing national examinations to get into good schools is directly related to their future jobs. The report did not provide figures on how the two groups scored in the math tests.
