<HEAD>Drug Related Parole Violations to be Reported Sooner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is tightening its drug regulations on federal parolees who used to get up to three chances to slip up and use drugs before the commission heard about it. The previous policy `` stated that when any three violations occurred in a 12-month period, the probation officer did n't have to notify us until after the three violations occurred,'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marble </PERSON>, the commission's director of case operations and program development. `` Now we require it immediately,'' she said Monday. `` As soon as the first drug violation occurs, they have to notify us.'' The new procedures are effective immediately. Affected by the new rules are about 12,900 people on parole and 2,500 who were required to serve their full sentences less good time off, she said. The latter are under <ORGANIZATION> Parole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> supervision until the end of their original sentences. They are supervised by about 2,220 probation officers. `` The reason that it's so important to find out immediately if these people are using drugs is because they commit criminal behavior to support their drug addiction,'' Ms. <PERSON> Marble </PERSON> said. `` It's a very expensive habit and they have to get the money for it somewhere,'' she said. `` Most of them do n't have jobs or good enough jobs to pay for the drugs, and it's important to get those people off the streets to protect the public.'' Parolees who have had a history of drug abuse `` are required to submit to urinalysis, to participate in drug counseling sessions and, on occasion, to be placed in an inpatient drug treatment program,'' Ms. <PERSON> Marble </PERSON> said. Not all parolees found to have used drugs, missed a counseling appointment or failed or refused to submit a urine sample would be sent back to prison, she said. The commission has a range of options from returning the parolee to prison immediately after a hearing to sending him to a community-based drug-treatment center, she said. Ms. <PERSON> Marble </PERSON> estimated that 50 percent of federal prisoners are confined for drug charges _ drug dealing to money-laundering _ but these rules are aimed at those among them who use drugs. The new procedures were approved by the commission 7-0 at a Feb. 8 meeting but not announced until Monday.
