<HEAD>Crisis in Relations Drags on; Election Seen as Rigged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the prospect of a rigged election perpetuating the rule of <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, administration officials and other experts see little hope of any thaw in U.S.-Panamanian relations. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s ruling coalition has selected a <LOCATION> Noriega </LOCATION> confidant, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Duque </PERSON>, as the official candidate in the May 7 election, an indication that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> intends to continue running the government from behind the scenes, much as he has for the past five years. This is causing headaches for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy makers, who see <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> as one of the major hemispheric issues facing the new administration, ranking alongside debt, drug trafficking and Marxist penetration of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as priority problems. A prime concern is the continued smooth functioning of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Almost nothing has gone right for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> since relations began to deteriorate in June 1987. A year ago, administration officials confidently predicted <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> would quickly fall after a series of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions were imposed. But <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> commander who is under indictment in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug smuggling charges, has survived the challenge, leaving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials perplexed and divided on what to do next. Gen. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON>, the Panama-based commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, has taken the unusual step of goin