nst him. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> may be faced with a choice of calling off the election or engaging in massive fraud to ensure victory, leaving him in a difficult position both at home and internationally, <PERSON> Gershman </PERSON> said. Ambassador <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, a captain of the anti-Noriega forces in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, agreed that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> may have to confront that unhappy choice. `` Nobody believes the election will be a solution in the struggle,'' <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON> was appointed by ousted President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as ambassador, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to recognize both. In February 1988, <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> but instead was deposed by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s allies hours later. Latin American democracies have kept a diplomatic distance from the Noriega-led government, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has shunned virtually all dealings with it. This has created a variety of problems for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, including obtaining such mundane items as license plates and driver's licenses. To minimize hardship, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has sharply reduced its staff in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and additional cuts are under consideration.
