ANIZATION>'s G-2 intelligence section. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 and spent most of his career in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> working as an analyst of intercepted radio and telephone traffic and coded messages. Hall pleaded guilty under an agreement that prohibits the government from seeking the death penalty. The maximum punishment he could receive is life in prison, forfeiture of all pay and allowances, dishonorable discharge and a fine. A still-secret part of the plea agreement outlines the sentence that Hall will receive unless the presiding judge, who is not permitted to see the sentencing agreement, imposes a lighter sentence. If the judge imposes a sentence that is harsher than the one in the agreement, the agreement will prevail. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> waived his right to a grand jury-type hearing to determine if a court-martial was warranted and agreed to be tried by a single military judge rather than a panel of officers. He also agreed to submit to `` unlimited debriefing'' and polygraph examination by government officials and to testify, if called, at grand jury proceedings against <PERSON> Huseyin </PERSON> <PERSON> Yildirim </PERSON>, a Turkish-born, naturalized citizen to whom <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> allegedly passed the classified information. The plea agreement requires that Hall sign away any profits he might earn in the future from any publication based on his involvement in the espionage case. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said through a military spokesman that he would not comment on <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s motivation for passing classified information until after <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> has been questioned by <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON> during the closed part of the court-martial.
