<SECOND>PM-Solar Flare,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massive Flare from Sun Disrupts Communications, May Affect Satellites</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: May be topped.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the most intense solar flares since 1984 could still be making itself felt Wednesday by triggering the aurora borealis and giving faulty commands to satellites. The massive flare erupted Monday on the eastern edge of the sun, sending a burst of radiation that interfered with a navigation system and some communications, federal officials said. Officials expected havoc early today as a result of a burst of high-energy particles from the flare, which they said could affect some aircraft communication and television signals. Forecaster <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunches </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, said the flare was beyond the measuring capacity of the agency's GOES satellites. He estimated the solar eruption was the most powerful since April 1984. The flare, detected at 9:05 a.m. EST, affected the Loran navigation system of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and disrupted some short-wave radio communications. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckman </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION> center, said another effect, called a geomagnetic storm, may arrive at Earth about 9 a.m. EST Wednesday. A geomagnetic storm is a wave of magnetically charged particles smashing into the Earth's magnetic field, disrupting natural currents and triggering the aurora borealis, or northern lights. The storm also slightly heats the atmosphere, causing it to expand. This, in turn, can affect the flight paths of satellites in relatively low orbits. The geomagnetic storm, said <PERSON> Heckman </PERSON>, also could energize particles trapped in the Earth's magnetic field. If these particles hit a satellite, he said, it could cause the craft to receive stray signals or faulty commands. <PERSON> Heckman </PERSON> said the flare occurred on the eastern edge of the sun, which means that much of the radiation will not affect the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> directly. The same area of the sun that spawned the flare, however, is rotating closer into view. `` Over the next two weeks we could more more vulnerable to more flares,'' he said. The sun goes through phases of intense activity. It passed a low point in 1986 and is now climbing toward an expected peak in intensity later this year or early in 1990. A flare occurs when energy stored by the sun's magnetic fields suddenly becomes unstable and is converted to heat and radiation within a few minutes, <PERSON> Heckman </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> solar telescopes recorded a flare of particles rising some 70,000 miles from the surface of the sun.
</TEXT>
