</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Crothers </PERSON> thought his pet lizard was a goner until he began hearing about sightings of a creature variously described by frightened residents as a 6-foot alligator or a diminuitive Godzilla. Then he knew that <PERSON> Cleopatra </PERSON>, his 3 -LCB- - foot Nile monitor lizard, was alive and leaping `` I had already supposed she was dead or someone had stolen her. But when I heard a few months ago about this thing people were seeing, I knew right away,'' he said. Animal control officers captured <PERSON> Cleopatra </PERSON> on Saturday after a resident reported seeing the lizard. <PERSON> Crothers </PERSON> no longer has room in his life for the reptile, though, so he sold the lizard to a woman for $ 75 on Sunday. `` I have a 10-month-old daughter and my wife does n't want it around the baby,'' he said. `` I do n't have the money to go buy it a new cage, and anyway, I ca n't keep pets at the apartment I have now. It's three strikes and you're out.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FREDERICK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
