<NOTE>FDA Warns About Garlic Mix</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some commercial and homemade chopped garlic and oil mixes can cause potentially fatal botulism if left at room temperature, the federal government warns. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> also asked producers of the commercial products to review their labeling to assure that the need for refrigeration is clearly marked on shipping cartons and the product containers. The warnings follow an investigation in <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, last month in which two men and a woman were hospitalized with botulism after a dinner at the home of one of the victims. The three had eaten a chopped garlic and oil mix that had been used in a spread for garlic bread, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency said garlic and oil mixes containing little or no acidifying agent such as phosphoric or citric acid should be kept refrigerated at all times _ from manufacture to consumption. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> studies have shown that garlic in an oil mixture can support growth of clostridium botulinum bacteria, whose spores produce a deadly toxin under certain conditions. Botulism is characterized by blurred or double vision, speech and breathing difficulty and progressive paralysis. Without prompt and correct treatment, a third of those diagnosed with it may die, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. Preliminary findings in the <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION> incident being investigated by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> implicated a commercially prepared mix called Colavita Chopped Garlic in Extra Virgin Olive Oil, distributed by <ORGANIZATION> Colavita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pasta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The firm is recalling the product and told <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> officials that distribution was discontinued more than a year ago, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said.
