<HEAD>Conservative GOP Senator Won't Seek Third Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> says a man can take only so much of `` meeting presidents and meeting prime ministers and spending hundreds of billions of dollars a year,'' and is calling it quits after this term. `` You only get one life, and I did n't want to spend the rest of my productive years in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said the 48-year-old Republican, who describes himself as the most conservative voice in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. He said he would return to private life, although he did not rule out a future run for office. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, with two years left on his six-year term, said he was making his decision public now to give potential <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidates a chance to raise money needed for the race. `` I have to admit I was very tempted to run again, not withstanding my pledge of old to limit myself to two terms,'' <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> said. `` Power, after all, is not only corrupting ... but it's addictive. It's fun exercising power; politics is fun.'' The problem, he said, is `` you get caught up with it, meeting presidents and meeting prime ministers and spending hundreds of billions of dollars a year. ... `` You lose touch with the real world,'' he said. `` I do n't think I've reached that part yet, but I think it could happen in a third term.'' A former airline pilot who never considered himself a politician, <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> had never held office before he ran for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1978 and pulled a stunning upset over Democratic incumbent <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON>. He easily won re-election in 1984, and would have been considered the favorite to win again in 1990 in a heavily Republican state. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> occasionally criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for softening its stance against communism and supporting a congressional pay raise. But his voice has been heard the loudest as an opponent of abortion and the pay raises and as a supporter for the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> rebels. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> has consistently been given 100 ratings by conservative groups that monitor <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> votes and zero ratings by liberal groups. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> called <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> a `` wonderful institution, but human nature mucks it up an awful lot.'' He complained that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is deteriorating because it is `` becoming more and more powerful at the expense of the presidency.'' `` We used to hear about the imperial presidency,'' he said. `` Nowadays, we're hearing about the imperial <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.''
