<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0770,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mikhail Baryshnikov Stars in `Metamorphosis' on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs with other New York reviews; No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Misha </PERSON> talks! Yes, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> has as much stage presence as a theater actor as he does as a dance superstar. He proves it in `` Metamorphosis,'' a riveting adaptation of <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s short novel that arrived Monday night at Broadway's <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrymore </PERSON> Theater. <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> is fine. But the real star of the evening is director and adaptor <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON>, who imposes a theatrical unity on the play that is astonishing. Every component of this stylized production serves the script brilliantly _ from setting to costumes to lighting to music to movement to acting. There is a seamlessness to this production, a quality that also enhanced <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON>'s provocative staging of `` Coriolanus,'' which played recently at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Shakespeare Festival. Still, most theatergoers will focus their attention on <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON>. In his first dramatic stage role, he portrays <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON> <PERSON> Samsa </PERSON>, a hard-working traveling salesman who wakes up one morning and finds he is turning into an insect, a dung beetle to be specific. You'd expect his physical movements to be superb, and they are. Dressed in a striped waistcoat and knickers and wearing wire-rimmed spectacles, <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> epitomizes <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s beleaguered little man, while at the same time suggesting the insect. He uses his feet, hands, arms and legs to mime his gradual change into the bug. It's a startling transformation, powerful, unnerving, yet touched with pity. But <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> also is in command of his voice, using it to great effect in sorrow _ listen to him call out for his mother _ and in humor, particularly when he munches the food thrown to him by his horrified family. The action, lasting some 95 minutes without intermission, unfolds on a raked stage with black lines radiating across a gray floor. The scenic supervisor is <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Durfee </PERSON>. A large skeleton of black metal bars shaped like a spider fans out across the playing area. Three spider-like stools are strewn across the footlights. Upstage, above a small ramp, is a cage where <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON> spends much of the evening watching his family. There are no props. Everything is suggested rather than played realistically. Three other actors, portraying <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON>'s family, share the stage with <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> for the entire play. Each is a distinctive, memorable character. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Auberjonois </PERSON> plays the father, a gruff bully fearful of losing his son's meal ticket, while <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Esterman </PERSON> is right on the edge _ and on target _ as the loving yet fearful mother. <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> exudes a steel reserve as <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON>'s faithful sister. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreindel </PERSON> and <PERSON> T.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> offer fine comic cameos as an outraged chief clerk and a fussy lodger. In a way, they all scurry like insects in a frenzy over <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON>'s hideous transformation. <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON> sees `` Metamorphosis'' as an existential horror story with no way out for the tormented <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON> or for the other, almost hysterical characters. The director captures that mood of desolation through dramatic use of lighting, supervised here by <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Nason </PERSON>. There are several episodes when giant shadows play across the back wall of the set, giving the drama a nightmarish quality. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spivack </PERSON>'s music contributes to that tension, building in volume as the family realizes what has happened to <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON> and what eventually must be done to get rid of him. <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON>'s production ends on a poignant note. The final image _ <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> curled up in almost a fetal position _ is haunting. But then the whole show is a series of haunting images, pictures that reinforce <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s striking story of what society does to those who are more than a little different. In other reviews, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> wrote in The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Times: `` It's hard to guess who will suffer most ... devotees of <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>, whose story is distorted into Marxist kitsch by this adaptation, or fans of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON>, whose stage debut as a dramatic actor, however dignified, amounts to little more than a sideshow to the loud circus surrounding him. `` <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON> never lets the human dimension disappear, however surreal the situation,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> wrote in the Daily News. `` <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON>, on the other hand, never lets the human dimension appear at all. ... As an attempt to convey <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s world, <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON>'s adaptation is tiresome. As a piece of merchandising, though, it's a triumph.'' `` The <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON> play itself is an expressionist impression of the <LOCATION> Kafka </LOCATION> original _ with little of the finite detail that makes the <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON> so chilling and moving,'' wrote <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. `` ... However, whatever objections one may have to <PERSON> Berkoff </PERSON> as an adaptor, his work here as director is fascinating and unquestionably effective.''
</TEXT>
