<HEAD>Real-life Hometown of Mayberry Star Victim of Technical Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Well gol-l-l-l-y! Not only was Sheriff <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s hometown of Mayberry mythical; the hometown of actor <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>, who created the role, has n't existed for decades. Mount Airy has been in a Twilight Zone. As a result of a typographical error, the city's charter was inadvertently repealed by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> on March 29, 1967. That means that such official acts as tax levies, elections and town expenditures have n't been valid _ technically _ since then. `` Whoops,'' said state Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamont </PERSON>. `` Legally, the whole town has n't existed for 22 years.'' To patch things up, <PERSON> Diamont </PERSON> has introduced a bill to validate all acts by the <LOCATION> Surry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> municipality's town board since the foul-up. Legislative officials are n't sure who made the mistake, but believe it apparently occurred in drafting legislation or in putting the law on the books. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, director of bill drafting for the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, said staffers recently spotted the error after <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airy </ORGANIZATION> officials asked about a law concerning the appointment of the tax collector. `` We found the disappearance of Mount Airy while doing research,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. `` I would n't be surprised if there were other missing cities out there.''
