<TEXT>
 Visionaries in this aging small town wanted to bring profits to <LOCATION> Prophetstown </LOCATION> to save it, so they went out and bought a company. `` We figured if we did n't grow, we'd die,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> `` Bud'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, 58, a hog hauler and president of <ORGANIZATION> Prophetstown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which brought <ORGANIZATION> Clear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to this community of 2,100. `` It's going to take something like this to keep small towns alive, revived, or whatever you want to call it,'' he said. `` As you go around <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> you can smell death.'' <LOCATION> Clear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> has eight workers who saw, sand and spray finish on oak furniture patterned after designs of the 18th and 19th century. The furniture sells in 14 states, especially the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. With the federal government's approval, local officials created PMI, sold $ 10 shares and made an offer to <PERSON> Darrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Milsap </PERSON>: You need the capital, we want your furniture. <PERSON> Milsap </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON>, packed up the company and moved 75 miles from <LOCATION> Granville </LOCATION> in north-central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> to the banks of the <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Whiteside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, where they manage the business now owned by <ORGANIZATION> PMI </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's very difficult to keep a small town going,'' said <LOCATION> Clear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>'s chief assembler, <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Proeger </PERSON>, 34, turning off his electric saw to talk about the company and the future of his hometown, population 2,100, about 140 miles west of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` I like living in small, rural communities. There's more of a relationship between citizens. In big cities people do n't talk to one another.'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, believes the furniture company has boosted the town's pride. When <ORGANIZATION> PMI </ORGANIZATION> was selling stock to make the purchase of <LOCATION> Clear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> possible, it posted signs that said, `` Buy A Share In Prophetstown's Future.'' Many did. `` The spirit has returned,'' said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, who noted that residents, many of whom are elderly, recently voted twice over 12 months to raise their taxes. `` People keep their lawns mowed and their bushes trimmed. Pride _ it's an ingredient I sure appreciate. I know it sounds a little hokey, but that's what it's all about.'' PMI hopes to add a few more small companies to <PERSON> Prophetstown </PERSON>'s economy, moves that would depend on the profits earned at <LOCATION> Clear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Clear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> had sales of $ 280,000. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> is projecting sales of $ 360,000 for 1989, and <PERSON> Milsap </PERSON> hopes to add a second shift. `` Sales have n't been a problem,'' said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>.
