of weather.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> says he commandeered an airliner in 1985 on command from his Amal militia superiors in the belief that the act might stop the factional bloodshed in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> also testified Monday that he had given a detailed confession to <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents who arrested him in 1987 because he was seasick, in shock and `` wanted to do anything so that they would just leave me alone.'' An appeals court has already ruled that the confession was valid, although defense attorney <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> has sought to convince the jury that it was improperly obtained because <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> was ill and without an attorney at the time. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> has not yet ruled whether he will instruct the jury to heed the defense argument that <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> was innocent because he was just following orders. Today's scheduled trial session was canceled because of hazardous conditions caused by snow and freezing rain. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>, 30, has pleaded innocent to a six-count indictment stemming from the hijacking of a <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jordanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, on June 11, 1985. No one was killed in the incident. The case is a test of a 1984 statute under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> asserts `` long-arm'' jurisdiction over the taking of American hostages abroad. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> said Monday that on June 10, 1985, the day before the hijacking, he was summoned to the office of <PERSON> Aqil </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamiyya </PERSON>, the military commander of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>