<HEAD>Activists Slam Government On 1,000th Day Of Emergency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-apartheid activists today accused the government of reneging on a promise to release a substantial number of detainees as <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> marked its 1,000 th day under a state of emergency `` We challenge the government to lift the state of emergency, because even that has failed to break the resistance of the people,'' said <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Valli </PERSON>, a former detainee and a spokesman for the banned <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition. <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> and other speakers at a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> news conference reiterated a call for the government to free all being held without charge. Some have been in custody the entire 1,000 days under emergency regulations. A group of detainees began a hunger strike Jan. 23, demanding to be released or put on trial. Hundreds in custody joined the strike, and Minister of Law and Order <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said Feb. 16 he would release a `` substantial number'' of detainees within two weeks. The government says it has freed 279 people held in South African prisons since then, and more than 500 people remain in detention. The Hunger Strike Support Committee said 202 detainees have been released and about 700 remain in prison. Many of those released have been placed under tight restrictions that limit their movements and prohibit them from participating in anti-government groups. `` Anger is growing among detainees, their parents, mass-based organizations and the community as a whole at <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>'s failure to honor his agreement,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Support </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. `` The general impression created as a result of his talks with lawyers, church leaders and detainees' parents was that well over half of the detainee population would be released,'' the statement added. More than 500 activists in detention have participated in the hunger strike, but most resumed eating when <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> promised the large scale releases. However, detainees in <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> have continued their fast and about 50 remain hospitalized nationwide, the <ORGANIZATION> Support </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said. The committee said detainees were considering rejoining the hunger strike and that sympathy fasts were being planned around the country. A spokesman for <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mellet </PERSON>, said the law and order minister was `` looking at each detainee's case individually.'' An estimated 30,000 people, almost all black, have been detained for varying lengths of time under the state of emergency declared by President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> on June 12, 1986. The government has banned most black-led anti-apartheid groups since the emergency went into effect. Some 4,000 people have died since widespread unrest erupted in September 1984. Most deaths occurred before the nationwide state of emergency was declared, although there has been ongoing black-on-black faction fighting in <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>. Police said today five blacks were killed overnight in unrest around the southeastern city of <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, where most of the fighting has occurred. The state of emergency gives security forces widespread powers and prohibits most forms of peaceful protest. Censorship rules imposed under the emergency restrict reporting about unrest and actions by security forces, but the measures have not been comprehensively enforced.
