<HEAD>Judge Pleads Guilty To Bribery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of three city judges charged after a federal bribery investigation pleaded guilty today in a deal that set her maximum sentence at five years in prison, court officials said. Recorder's Judge <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> was to have gone on trial today in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on charges of accepting $ 9,000 in bribes to fix two criminal cases and arrange for a convict's early release. The indictment also charged her with failing to report income from the bribes. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, 47, pleaded guilty to one count of extortion of $ 5,000 and to signing a false tax return for 1984, said a court spokeswoman who would not give her name. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> had faced 20 years in prison if convicted of bribery, and three years for filing a false tax return. No sentencing date was set. In the other bribery cases, a state district judge is serving a 10-year sentence and another judge was acquitted last week of four bribery charges but a mistrial was declared on a racketeering charge.
