<HEAD>Marxist PLO Leader Vows to Escalate Struggle Against Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leader of a <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> faction today said his group would increase guerrilla attacks against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, saying such actions were not included in the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s renunciation of terrorism. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference `` there is no resolution -LRB- by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- ... providing for a truce in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> between us and the Israelis.'' He said his guerrillas `` will not only keep up the armed struggle, but also will escalate it and diversify its forms and methods.'' He did not elaborate. His organization is the second-largest faction of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> after <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION>. In December, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ended a 13-year ban on public contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and initiated dialogue with <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> after he renounced terrorism and recognized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s announcement was more explicit than a statement issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s parliament-in-exile, in November. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>, has said military operations against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> were not considered terrorist acts. But he recently indicated he would be willing to negotiate a truce in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has said guerrilla attacks in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> could have a negative impact on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> - <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> dialogue There has been no progress in the talks since President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> took over in January. Since December, guerrillas have clashed three times with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops and their allies in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Ten guerrillas have been killed in the shootouts, but no Israelis have been hurt. Israeli officials have said that in all three cases, the guerrillas were planning to infiltrate into <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, but were uncovered while still in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s self-designated security zone in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> set up the buffer in 1985 when it removed the bulk of its forces, three years after invading <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Israeli jets have struck Palestinian targets in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> three times this year, killing two guerrillas and wounding 34 people.
