<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Electing a successor to socialist <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>'s mayor, a push to bring back the death penalty and a host of environmental issues were on the agenda today as <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> observed its annual Town Meeting Day. Voters braved wind chills of 43 degrees below zero to travel to their local town halls and settle affairs for another year. In <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, turnout was described as light to moderate. `` Maybe their cars, some of them probably would n't start this morning,'' said <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Poulin </PERSON>, an office assistant in City Clerk <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rader </PERSON>'s office. <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, population 38,000 and the nearest thing <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> has to a big city, will be choosing between a liberal Democrat and two candidates further to the left to replace <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>. The 47-year-old mayor, nationally known for outraged rhetoric against American corporate capitalism, is taking leave from politics, at least temporarily, to teach and write. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON>, who eschews the socialist label but is running under the banner of <ORGANIZATION> Sanders </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, is favored to win over Democrat <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chioffi </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Greens </ORGANIZATION> party candidate <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Baird </PERSON>. <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> initially angered many <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> backers by ducking even the Progressive label, calling himself only an `` independent'' in his first batch of campaign literature. But lately he has more clearly articulated the activist politics he helped execute as chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> under <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>. In about three dozen towns around <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, residents will be voting on a non-binding resolution asking the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to reinstate the death penalty, last used in the 1950s. On Monday night, at least six towns approved the death penalty resolution. It was tabled in one community and rejected in three, including <LOCATION> Rockingham </LOCATION>, where residents said they were afraid of sending an innocent person to the electric chair. At least nine towns will decide whether to form environmental conservation commissions. Nine communities already have such boards, which are volunteer groups created to protect a town's natural resources. In several other communities, voters may authorize selectmen to create funds with local taxes to protect land resources such as farmland, waterfront property and scenic areas. Several towns approved resolutions expressing worries about a proposed pipeline to bring natural gas from western <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Rockingham </LOCATION>, where the proposed line would go through a historic cemetery and two church parking lots, residents approved a resolution to examine the safety and economic need for the line. In <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, residents approved a resolution giving them a say if the state tries to locate a proposed 15,000-seat sports and arts complex in their town. Proponents want the complex to keep the Volvo International Tennis Tournament in the state.
