pickup 2nd graf pvs, ``The session ...'' TRIMS thereafter to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity chairman <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> today met with Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and later reported progress in monthlong negotiations between the opposition and communist government. He announced the last session of the talks would be held April 3, and various working groups composed of experts will finish putting the final touches on the accord by March 20. The period between March 20 and April 3 would be devoted to reviewing the agreement, he said. `` All basic problems, like pluralism, ... will be achieved in time, in line with our commitments,'' said the Solidarity leader, looking cheerful after the eight-hour meeting with the leader of the government side in the talks. `` I am very satisfied.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> indicated agreement was reached on legalizing the three main banned independent organizations at issue in the talks _ the Solidarity trade union movement, the farmers' union Rural Solidarity and the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Agreements on `` all those organizations, a mininum of three'' will be achieved, he said. He said further talks with <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> might be necessary. `` We are removing obstacles that have appeared here and there. But we are only removing them politically, and the rest must be worked out at the -LRB- various working group -RRB- tables,'' he said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> spoke outside the Roman Catholic episcopate in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> after returning with a vanful of advisers from the meeting in a secluded government villa outside the capital. The session came the morning after a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> session that gave Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> qualified support for his policy of rapprochement with the opposition, government spokesma