<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A car bomb exploded near the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> today, killing two women and injuring 21 people, police said. Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>, a staunch ally of the Syrians who police west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, blamed the blast on the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> cabinet of Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>. The explosive-laden yellow <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> blew up in front of a fruit and vegetable stall at an intersection off a main commercial thoroughfare. One of the victims was killed as she maneuvered to park her car near the stand, police said. Another woman died at the hospital, said a police spokesman, who under standing regulations is not identified. The explosion started a fire involving several parked cars and shattered glass in surrounding buildings. Three people were evacuated by ambulance, and the police spokesman said `` civilians carried most of the casualties on their backs to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> hospital,'' several hundered yards away. <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> charged at a news conference that the bomb was part of a campaign by the Christian cabinet to choke private militias in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` Those who are trying to encircle us, today sent us a booby-trapped message,'' <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> told a news conference at his family's ancestral palace in <LOCATION> Mukhtara </LOCATION>, southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Tensions between <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s rival <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> and Moslem cabinets have increased since Monday, when <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> ordered the army to block merchant ships trying to dock at militia-controlled ports instead of those run by the government. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has said his move will cut off the main revenues of private armies. But his Syrian-backed Moslem rivals view it as an economic blockade of Moslem regions. At the scene of the blast, a witness who also spoke on condition of anonymity said he was in a building 150 feet away when the blast occurred. It shattered windows there. `` I was having my coffee. First, I felt the glass crumbling down, then I heard the blast.'' He said when he looked out of the window, he saw fires and a body lying in the street. Gunmen fired their rifles in the air to make way for the ambulances. It was the fourth car bombing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> this year. By police count, 11 people have been killed and 47 wounded in the previous three car bombings since Jan. 13. Last year, 116 people were killed and 488 wounded in 20 car bomb explosions across the country, plagued by a 14-year-old civil war. No group claimed any of the explosions, but Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> officials have blamed each other's militias for them.
