<HEAD>Soviet Nuclear-Powered Refused Three Port Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three Soviet Far Eastern ports, wary of nuclear power after the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> disaster, have refused to allow the docking of a nuclear-powered merchant ship that a newspaper today compared to a `` homeless child.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said the 858-foot-long Sevmorput has been anchored off <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> for four days because the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> refused it entry. The newspaper said city officials will not allow the ship to dock until they receive additional information about its radiation safety. Officials of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Nakhodka </LOCATION> and the coastal <LOCATION> Magadan </LOCATION> region have also rejected port calls by the ship, the newspaper said. The newspaper said fractures recently appeared in the $ 260 million ship, but that its `` atomic heart'' was not damaged. It did not say how the damage was inflicted. <PERSON> Sovietskaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossiya </PERSON> said the vessel was like a `` sea monster'' and a huge `` offended homeless child.'' On Saturday, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Vodny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> reported that a nuclear reactor meltdown nearly occurred last fall aboard another nuclear-powered ship, the icebreaker <PERSON> Rossiya </PERSON>. Public opposition to nuclear power has been mounting in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> since the April 26, 1986, explosion and fire at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. At least 31 people were killed in the accident, and a cloud of radiation spread worldwide.
