<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said today he is open to a `` sensible answer'' to the proliferation of semiautomatic assault weapons and has asked <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, his nominee for drug policy coordinator, to work on it. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, has said he opposes a ban on such guns. In a news conference today, he said he talked to <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> about the problem after <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> was quoted as saying he might favor curtailment of such weapons as a way to cut down on drug-related violence. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he told <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>: `` I'm not so rigid that if you come to me with a sensible answer that takes care of the concerns that I've felt over the years, I'll take a hard look at it, and I'll work with you to that end. He said he wants to find `` what can be worked out with finality on AK47s ... and still do what's right by the legitimate sportsman.'' `` It is n't as easy as it seems,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was to have gone to <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> today to speek on drugs, but the trip was scrapped due to the icy and snowy weather that battered the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. On Monday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> began a week devoted to an anti-drug message, appealing to military veterans to help combat narcotics by encouraging drug-education programs and anti-drug legislation at the state and local levels. `` You've fought for your nation once and your nation needs you again,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in an address Monday to several thousand people at a Veterans of Foreign Wars conference. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for $ 5.5 billion for the battle against drugs, with most of the money going to law enforcement efforts and border interdiction. His request for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 is 21 percent more than the $ 4.6 billion allocated for this year. It is $ 236 million more than former President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had sought in his first draft of the spending plan. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the veterans that drugs were `` a threat no less real than the adversaries you have battled.'' `` The notion that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is a nation at peace is only partly true, as long as the violence and destructive power of drugs assault our communities,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he will `` mobilize all our resources, wage this war on all fronts. We're going to combat drug abuse with education, treatment, enforcement ... interdiction and, yes, with our nation's armed services. Speaking of involvement by the military, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` when that prudently can be done and when that's what it takes, we are going to have to go all out.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had planned to carry his anti-drug message today to <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, but a storm along the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> caused him to cancel the trip. White House aides said it would be rescheduled, probably for next week. On another subject, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Monday that he supports `` lower levels of armaments'' in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but with a continued backup by nuclear weapons. `` For <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and its allies, a survivable nuclear force will remain the ultimate deterrent of aggression,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. His comments coincided with a proposal by the Kremlin for heavy reductions in troops and armor in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> also urged negotiations to eliminate all battlefield nuclear weapons from the continent.
