/PERSON>, who was referring to Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s visit during the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit meeting last summer, was one of several hundred guests at the reception. The Gorbachevs later attended a celebration held in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Bolshoi Theater to mark International Women's Day The ceremonies, broadcast on TV, showed Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> returning to the more traditional protocol role of the Soviet leader's wife. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> sat on the dais with other Politburo members and dignitaries, while his wife was in the audience. In a dispatch showing the limited political clout of women in Soviet society, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> also reported Tuesday that of 2,901 candidates running to represent territorial districts in a new national assembly, only 17 percent are women. Voters nationwide on March 26 will choose 1,500 deputies for the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, a new body that will elect the Soviet president and parliament. Organizations such as the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and trade unions are directly electing deputies to fill 750 other seats.
