<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     03-07 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milan Promises a Warm Winter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When next winter rolls around, no woman need worry that she will be left out in the cold. Italian designers showing their fall-winter 1989-90 collections here this week devote much of their creative talent to coats, from the pratical polo to dramatic capes and elegant dusters. The cut is as generous as it is cozy. Ample sleeves, huge shawl collars, and loosely pleated backs contribute to create a soft flowing effect. Most often belted at the waist, these outer coverings are either cropped at the hip, or so long they can double as street sweepers. The favorite fabric is wool, but leather and shearling also play heavily in the collections, not to mention fur, from fake to extravagant mink. Colors are warm fall shades ranging from forest greens, to vineyard reds and purples, to beiges and browns. The unpractical but dramatically stylish cape, often hooded like a medieval friar's, also makes a comeback. <PERSON> Ferragamo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Genny </PERSON>, who showed Tuesday, midway through the fashion week, count heavily on the coat for winter warmth. <PERSON> Ferragamo </PERSON> _ the Florentine family known for its town and country chic and its shoes _ presented a chocolate colored duster with super wide sleeves, tied at the waist, and a series of chic car coats with bright gold buttons. On the whole, the <PERSON> Ferragamo </PERSON> collection was very smart and sporty, with trim pants suits in black and white checkered patterns, and patchwork leather blazers and knee-length skirts for daytime, and sophisticated long sleeved silk jersey gowns, buttoned or unbuttoned at the back with gold buttons for evening. <PERSON> Genny </PERSON>, designed by <PERSON> Versace </PERSON> but more subdued than his presentation of micro miniskirts during his own collection Sunday night, presented the most opulent coat wear seen thus far on the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> runway, in his series of lavish mink wraps. These unabashedly expensive creations, made up no doubt of hundreds of skins to create the huge collar, ample sleeve and wide swirling hemline, go against the current conservationist trend for imitation furs in elegant styles, favored among others by <PERSON> Armani </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Emporio </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and <LOCATION> Moschino </LOCATION>. The Genny collection was snappy and young with a wide variety of pants ranging from man-tailored to tight-fitting jodhpurs, and short-cropped jackets. Skirts were a mere four inches above the knee, a conservative length for flamboyant <PERSON> Versace </PERSON>, but still had his trademark tight derriere. Evening at <ORGANIZATION> Genny </ORGANIZATION>'s is basically black, enriched by traditional pearl accessories, or an enticing rhinestone embroidered bustier peering out of a slinky chiffon gown.
</TEXT>
