<BYLINE>Will It Play in Lubbock? ^By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lubbock </PERSON> may be <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. He cited a fan from the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> city on Tuesday in defending the beginning of his administration, which some critics contend is getting off to a slow start. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told a White House news conference that he had `` talked to a fellow from <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the other day. ... And he said: ` All the people in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> think things are going just great.''' The reference to populatiry in a smaller city in the nation's midsection evoked memories of the phrase `` Will it play in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>? which became popular in the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration. If <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> is to replace <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> as the standard for middle <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> acceptance, let's see how the two compare, based on statistics reported in the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>'s `` County and City Data Book: 1988.'' <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> is physically bigger, with 106.3 square miles of land compared to just 42.2 square miles in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> has more people too, outnumbering its <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> companion 186,400 to 110,290. But <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> is a bit more crowded, at 2,614 people per square mile compared to 1,754 in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. The two cities are diverging in size. From 1980 to 1986, the Sun Belt city of <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> saw its population grow 7.2 percent. Over the same time, <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> lost 11.2 percent of its residents. In racial breakdown, the cities are somewhat similar. <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> has a population that is 81 percent white and 17 percent black, while <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> is 81 percent white and nearly 19 percent black. <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> has about 1 percent Asians to help make up the discrepancy. On the other hand, 19 percent of <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>'s residents are Hispanic, while this group makes up only 1.4 percent of the people in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. Hispanics can be of any race. <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> is older, with 12.3 percent of its people aged 65 and over, compared to 7.8 percent in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>'s birth rate is 20.1 births per 1,000 people, compared to 16.5 for <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, while the death rate is 9.8 per 1,000 in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> and 6.6 for <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> has a narrow lead in high school graduates, 69.6 percent of its residents compared to 69.3 percent in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. On the other hand, <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> counts 22.4 percent of its people with four years of college, compared to 16.5 percent in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. Per capita income in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> in 1985 was $ 11,140, compared to $ 10,452 for <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>, with 12.4 percent of the people in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> metropolis below the poverty level compared to 14.4 percent in the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> city. <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, in the midwestern farm belt, is twice as wet as the semiarid high plains city in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Rain averages nearly 35 inches annually in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> but only 17.7 inches in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> is also colder, with an average January low reading of 13.3 degrees Fahrenheit, compared to a low of 24.3 degrees for <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. But summers are hotter in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, with July's high averaging 91.0 degrees for <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> and 85.5 degrees for <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>.
