<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> requested help from the Army as fears mounted that three Japanese climbers trying to make a winter ascent of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McKinley </LOCATION> were near death somewhere near the summit. The Park Service on Tuesday said little can be done until hurricane-force winds buffeting the 20,320-foot peak abate. The climbers have not been heard from in more than a week and are believed to have run out of food six days ago, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinley </PERSON>, a park service spokesman. The men have a radio but have made no contact, he said. The Army has Chinook helicopters specially equipped for high-altitude rescues, but they are not expected to be able to fly until Thursday or Friday because of the wind, <PERSON> Quinley </PERSON> said. An Army plane circled the mountain repeatedly on Monday, broadcasting messages, but received no response from the climbers, <PERSON> Quinley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Quinley </PERSON> said park rangers believe the climbers could be holed up in a snow cave somewhere between 17,000 feet and the summit of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McKinley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s highest peak. He said there is also concern that the men have run out of fuel needed to melt snow. Without water, they could quickly succumb to dehydration and hypothermia. <PERSON> McKinley </PERSON>, because of its location near the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>, is judged to be one of the most difficult winter climbs. `` Based on what they took, they're six days out of food,'' <PERSON> Quinley </PERSON> said. `` But the park service has a cache at 17,200, apparently fairly close to where they would be camped, and there's food and fuel there. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported sustained winds of 60 mph to 100 mph in the area. Climbing ranger <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Seibert </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Talkeetna </LOCATION> estimated those winds reach 90 mph to 200 mph as they funnel through passes in the mountains. He identified the missing climbers as 39-year-old <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamada </PERSON>, the group leader, 31-year-old <PERSON> Teruo </PERSON> <PERSON> Saegusa </PERSON> and 34-year-old <PERSON> Kozo </PERSON> <PERSON> Komatsu </PERSON>, all of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>.
