<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A south-to-north `` Freedom Caravan'' will leave <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> in late June to commemorate the 25th anniversary of the slayings of three civil right workers in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, officials said today. The caravan will leave <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> on June 20 and arrive in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on June 24 for a memorial ceremony in the city where <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> is buried. The bodies of <LOCATION> Chaney </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> were found in an earthen dam in <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in 1964, six weeks after the young men had been reported missing. They had each been shot in the head. Although no one was ever tried for the murders, eight men were convicted on federal charges of denying the three their constitutional rights. The slayings and the aftermath were the subject of the movie `` Mississippi Burning,'' which received an Academy Award nomination. State Rep. <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, a black lawmaker and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>, said at a news conference that the caravan from <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> would be a symbol of a `` new foundation of human rights'' in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He said the events will include rallies in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> or Meridian and in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The caravan, including buses and cars, will proceed through <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and then to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> called the commemoration an important event to symbolize c