<HEAD>New Orleans Symphony Shakes Off Debt And Serves Up Chopin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON> will raise the baton before a sold-out house Wednesday night in a concert that backers hope signals the end of years of debt and discord for the New Orleans Symphony. The symphony suspended operation a year ago, unable to pay its musicians and nearly $ 4 million in debt. It is reopening with the help of volunteers, corporate gifts, donated services and free rent for five years, its president said Tuesday. `` I'm elated,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who assumed the job of bailing out the orchestra in December. `` We have put together a wonderful staff that has been working 24 hours a day doing what everyone said could n't be done.'' The financial crisis had been building for years and was blamed on mismanagement before the symphony got a full-time manager in 1986. Public and corporate financial support eroded and the money problems led to a musicians walkout in 1987. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Coca-Cola Bottling, was picked to head the symphony board and engineer a comeback. `` It really got to people in this city when the symphony was dark. They realized what they were in danger of losing and decided to make sure it would n't happen,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> also helped the city during last summer's Republican National Convention. He took over a faltering private fund drive and helped raise the $ 5 million needed to pay <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' cost of serving as host. Donations of $ 225,000, earmarked for the symphony if it reopened, will pay off the remaining debts and leave the books in the black Thursday morning, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. The symphony's home, the Orpheum Theater, is being completely restored and has been sold to seven investors, eliminating $ 2.4 million of the symphony's debts, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. The investors, who have asked not to be identified, have agreed to let the symphony use the theater for free for five years. `` The work on the theater has been done by volunteers and contractors who have donated their services for the most part,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. In addition to eliminating the debt, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said the symphony had two other goals _ selling out their first performance and 50 percent sales of the subscription tickets. `` Our opening concert has been sold out for over a week and our subscription sales are running at 80 percent,'' he said. <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON>, music director of the symphony, will conduct a program of <PERSON> Chopin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Brahms </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> in the reopening concert. It will be the third season for the son of the Russian composer <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON>.
