<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb hidden in a car exploded during the Tuesday morning rush hour near the American University hospital in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, killing two women and wounding 21, police said. Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> blamed the bomb on Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, charging its was part of the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> leader's efforts to neutralize the war-torn nation's private armies. `` I looked out of the window and saw fire blazing in several cars, a corpse in the middle of the street and people running in all directions,'' said a man who watched the blast form a nearby building. He refused to give his name. The fourth car bomb in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> this year was placed in a yellow <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> that exploded in front of a fruit and vegetable stall off the main <LOCATION> Hamra </LOCATION> commercial thoroughfare. A woman maneuvering to park her car near the yellow <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> was killed when the bomb went off, a police spokesman said. The blast threw her body from the car. He said the second woman, a passer-by, suffered serious head wounds and died later in the hospital. The bomb triggered fires in nine cars parked near the stall and shattered windows in surrounding buildings. Panicking motorists caused several accidents as the tried to flee the scene, said a woman who identified herself only as a telephone operator from the nearby Cavalier Hotel. Ambulances were slowed by rush-hour traffic, the police spokesman said. Accountant <PERSON> Jamal </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamoud </PERSON> said he watched as `` gunmen fired their rifles in the air to make way for the ambulances.'' Ambulances evacuated only three of the wounded. `` Civilians carried most of the casualties on their backs to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> hospital,'' a few hundred yards away, the police spokesman said. Most of those injured suffered minor cuts from glass shards, he said. <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> militia is allied with the Syrians who police west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, said the bomb was a warning from <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>. `` Those who are trying to encircle us, today sent us a booby-trapped message,'' <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> claimed. He was referring to efforts by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s helicopter gunships and gunboats to prevent merchant ships from docking at illegal port facilities run by his and other militias along <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s coastline. The air-and-sea patrols started Monday, ignoring rocket fire by <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s militia based near <LOCATION> Jiye </LOCATION> port, south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s aim to choke off the main revenues of private armies has provoked objections from Syrian-backed Moslem leaders who consider it an attempt to restrict their operations. Moslems refuse to recognize <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s military Cabinet, appointed by outgoing President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> in September after parliament failed to elect his successor. They pledge allegiance to the Moslem Cabinet of Acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, who governed under <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>. By police count, 11 people were killed and 47 wounded in three January car bombings. Twenty car bombs exploded in 1988, killing 116 people and wounding 488.
