<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asserted Tuesday that he is as committed to human rights as former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had been, even though <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did n't publicly focus on the issue during his recent trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` I think quiet discussion is a good approach to try to effect the human rights objectives that I feel very strongly about,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told a White House news conference. The president defended his conduct in not making a big issue of an incident in which Chinese police prevented dissident <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> from attending a barbecue in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> last week hosted by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> had been on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s invitation list. `` The very invitation to that dissident that they thoroughly disapproved of shows our public commitment to it -LRB- human rights -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> raised human rights issues in each of his meetings with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and once invited a group of Soviet dissidents to meet with him in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. On a trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1984, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> protested angrily when <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities censored parts of his nationally televised address, including a portion dealing with religion. Still, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sought to draw a parallel between his own presentation of human-rights concerns in meetings with foreign leaders and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s approach. `` You know, there's two schools of how you do the human rights agenda,'' he said. `` I think that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was correct when he raised the human rights agenda with the Soviets privately rather than beating his breast and doing it publicly.'' `` And I think the results have been rather penetrating, still a long way to go with the Soviets,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. During his <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> trip, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had not raised the issues of human rights with Chinese leaders _ presumably including the key issue of human rights in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, scene of recent clashes between police and rioters seeking independence from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Tuesday imposed martial law in the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> after three days of anti-Chinese rioting. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday said that the press secretary's statement was true up the point that <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> spoke, but that he later raised the general issue in a private meeting with Chinese senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaopeng </PERSON>. `` It was raised by me personally,'' he said. On the subject of linking economic concessions to the Soviets to human-rights progress, including an easing of emigration restrictions on Soviet Jews, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` There's clearly got to be some linkage.'' `` When Soviets come out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, which happened here not so long ago, give them credit for that. When you get some lightening up a little bit on the question of Soviet Jews or something of that nature, give some credit,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said.
