<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Roman Catholic church official says he expects `` points of difference'' to emerge between the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and American bishops but no confrontation in an extraordinary meeting beginning Wednesday. `` There will be probably, in any free-flowing discussion, points of difference _ points of difference that will be discussed and faced,'' said Archbishop <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>. He did n't go into specifics, but there have been differences over the right of Catholics to dissent from church teaching to how much weight bishops' conferences should have. Thirty-five <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prelates gathered Tuesday in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on the eve of the four-day meeting with Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II and top <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bishops originally had requested the meeting in 1986, when tensions with the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> were high over its disciplining of several clergy members considered too permissive on such issues as ministering to homosexual groups and artificial birth control, which the church bans. As tensions eased in recent years, the bishops considered dropping the request. However, the pope wanted the meeting held, according to <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>. In his speeches to <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholics </ORGANIZATION>, the pontiff has expressed concern about people who disagree with church teaching and practice what <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials call `` cafeteria Catholicism'' _ obeying some doctrines and ignoring others. In this week's meetings, he and other <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials are expected to encourage the bishops to be ardent proponents of church teaching in a secular society. Cardinal <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON>, the West German who heads the powerful Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, will deliver a major address Wednesday that is expected to set the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s tone for the meeting. A <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> source described it as a `` thought-provoking'' talk. <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials stress the meeting wo n't be confrontational. May said the bishops hoped to bring to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> a better understanding of the 52 million-member <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's been a lack of understanding on the part of some people -LRB- in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' he said in an interview Tuesday. `` Some of these men have not been in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or not very much ... some of them have n't been as fully conversant with our ways of doing things in a cultural contest.'' He said he hoped for a `` deeper understanding of separation of church and state, a deeper understanding of the freedom of thought in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ... a deeper understanding of the democratic process that we're used to, which is not always the way things are done in the church.'' He added that the pope `` seems to have gotten a new vision'' of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from his trips there and meetings with American bishops last year. `` I think it -LRB- the meeting -RRB- will be significant in the life of the church,'' said May. `` It will probably build a stronger sense of unity between the <LOCATION> Vatican