<BYLINE>Soviet Pacific Ports Rebuff Attempts by Nuclear-Powered Ship to
Dock ^By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Soviet Far East ports and a nearby region have refused entry to a nuclear-powered Soviet merchant ship for fear it is radioactive, and a newspaper likened the vessel Tuesday to a `` homeless child.'' The 860-foot Sevmorput, launched only months ago, had been anchored off <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> for four days because the city council refused entry, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said. It said city officials decided March 2 not to let the ship dock until they receive additional information about its radiation safeguards. Officials of <LOCATION> Nakhodka </LOCATION> and the nearby <LOCATION> Magadan </LOCATION> region also refused port calls after tens of thousands of residents protested to a radio station, the newspaper said. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, the government daily, reported on opposition to the Sevmorput on March 2. A report in a third newspaper Saturday said said a meltdown in a nuclear reactor on another Soviet ship was narrowly averted. The Sovietskaya Rossiya article indicated residents became fearful of the Sevmorput because they had not been given details about problems with it. Fractures appeared in the $ 260 million barge carrier soon after it began its maiden voyage Dec. 31 from the <LOCATION> Crimean </LOCATION> port of Kerch to the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, the newspaper said. Experts rushed in to check whether radiation was released and found the ship clean, confirming its `` atomic heart'' was not damaged, the article said. It did not say how the damage occurred or precisely when the incident occurred. According to the newspaper, the ship has good safeguards and could even withstand the crash of a jetliner or a collision with a huge icebreaker, but it added: `` A deficit of information, piled on top of the invisible shadow of the Chernobyl tragedy and the most complex ecological situation in the region, detonated a powerful explosion of public indignation.'' Public opposition to nuclear power has grown since the explosion and fire April 26, 1986, at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. At least 31 people were killed and the plant spewed radioactivity that eventually spread around the world. Authorities are closing a nuclear power plant in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, a region prone to earthquakes, and have canceled plans to expand other plants. <PERSON> Sovietskaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossiya </PERSON> said the Sevmorput was like a `` sea monster,'' uneconomical because of its size. It said the ship would lose $ 19.3 million this year and $ 22.9 million in 1990. It described the vessel to an `` offended homeless child'' and said every day it is idle costs $ 88,525. On Saturday, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Vodny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> said a reactor meltdown nearly occurred Nov. 11 on the icebreaker Rossiya while it was docked at the northern port of <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>. It said operator error was responsible.
