<HEAD>Annunzio Says Commemorative Coin-Sales Law Cuts National Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill., says the national debt has been reduced by about $ 750 million through sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commemorative coins and related programs but more must be done `` to get this terrible debt under control. <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee on consumer affairs and coinage, says a law earmarking profits from sales of commemorative coins to reduce the national debt has been `` a step in the right direction, but we need to take a lot of steps to pay off this debt,'' which now stands at about $ 2.7 trillion. `` We've got to earmark tax money or even have a surtax. I know some people wo n't like to hear that talk about a surtax, but we've got to get this terrible debt under control It's the biggest, most serious problem facing this country today,'' <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> said Monday. A law passed in 1982 authorizing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mint to sell gold and silver coins and use proceeds for debt retirement and other special purposes `` is my own small way of dealing with the problem,'' <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> said. According to the subcomittee, which <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> headed for a decade, profits from the sales are approaching $ 960 million. Of that, it said $ 742 million is money to reduce the debt and $ 214 million is for special programs _ support of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic athletes and restoration of the Statue of Liberty and <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. The debt-reduction figure includes $ 409 million from profits on commemorative coins, $ 200 million from sales of gold and silver coins, $ 25 million last year from special collector coin sets and a projected profit of $ 108 million from the 1988 Olympic coin program. `` There was no coin program before I became chairman,'' <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> said. `` Now, we have this clicking on all cylinders. ... I just hope to God it does n't go down the drain.'' He said private marketers of coins and precious metals opposed the legislation when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> first considered it, `` and they'll never give up, especially now that I'm gone. `` I do n't think there's all that much support for private enterprise to take over,'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Niro </PERSON>, a dealer at the <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in Silver Spring, Md. `` Personally, as both a dealer and a collector, I'm very happy with the way things are now,'' he said Tuesday. `` The government makes a profit. So do we. ... It's been a good for everyone involved.'' <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> left the coinage panel chairmanship this year to become chairman of the subcommittee on financial institutions supervision, regulations and insurance.
