ich </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION> state, was the site of the Nazi party's annual rallies. <PERSON> Jahn </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> chose <ORGANIZATION> Nuremberg </ORGANIZATION> because it was a traditional government conference site before the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> took over, and `` <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> wanted to give the impression they had ties with tradition.'' To further cement that impression, <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> commissioned his chief architect, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Speer </PERSON>, to construct the coliseum and a stadium to hold 450,000 people at <LOCATION> Nuremberg </LOCATION>. The large stone facade of the incomplete building is located on the outskirts of the city. The area was to be the site of columned structures, stadiums and parks, inspired by architecture in ancient <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> wanted the complex to reflect the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>' interest in architecture and to commemorate the Third Reich, which he boasted would survive a thousand years. It ended in ruins in 1945 after 12 years.
