<SECOND>AM-Solar Flare,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massive Flare from Sun Disrupts Communications, May Affect Satellites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Another high-intensity flare spewed from the sun Tuesday, but federal officials said it was not as massive as an eruption Monday that interfered with a radio navigation system and some communications. Forecaster <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> said the new flare was classed as an X-1, far weaker than the earlier one but `` still pretty significant.'' Solar flares are massive eruptions that burst suddenly from the face of the sun. The eruptions send waves of electromagnetic radiation and charged particles out into space. These waves can disrupt communications on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and trigger brilliant displays of the aurora, or polar lights. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> said Monday's flare overpowered instruments aboard <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> satellites that are able to measure solar intensity only up to what is called X-12. Initially, experts estimated the flare at an X-20, but that has been revised. `` A more thorough review of the data came up with an estimate of about X-15,'' said <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>. `` That's still an exceptional flare'' and is the most powerful since April 1984. A powerful burst of X-rays and ultraviolet radiation, which crosses the 92 million miles between <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and the sun in just eight minutes, was detected about 9:05 a.m. EST Monday. It disrupted a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loran </ORGANIZATION> navigation system and some short wave radio communications, officials said. At the <ORGANIZATION> Goddard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which monitors the Solar Max Satellite for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, officials reported that a stream of radiation from Monday's solar flare briefly overpowered the satellite instruments. `` The satellite -LRB- Solar Max -RRB- was stunned for about a minute and then recovered,'' said <PERSON> Carolynne </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. The Solar <PERSON> Max </PERSON> satellite focuses instruments on the sun to gather data for scientists. Monday's flare may have created a storm of geomagnetic energy that could impact the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> sometime late Tuesday or early Wednesday morning, said <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>. He said the storm is expected to be `` major to severe'' in the latitudes near both of the Earth's poles, and `` minor'' in the mid-latitudes. The storm could last for two to three days, <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> said. `` Major to severe'' geomagnetic storms can block some radio and navigation communications between aircraft and ground stations, and can interfere with some long distance telephone service by generating an electrical charge along cables. The areas of Earth apt to be most affected by the major to severe storm, he said, are those above 65 degrees latitude. This would include much of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, and the far northern parts of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. South of the equator, only <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> is above 65 degrees. Geomagnetic storms also create spectacular natural light shows by energizing the Earth's magnetic fields over the north and south poles. This creates the aurora, known north of the equator as the Northern Lights. Radiation from solar flares also can affect orbiting satellites, but Ms. <PERSON> White </PERSON> said there were no reports at Goddard of any instrument problems from solar radiation. <PERSON> Goddard </PERSON> monitors up to 21 satellites for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. Bursts of solar radiation can affect satellite orbits by causing the Earth's atmosphere to heat and expand slightly. This can put molecules of atmospheric gases into contact with satellites in low orbits and cause the craft to slow slightly and drop lower. More solar flares may occur at any time during the next 10 to 11 days, <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> forecasters said. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> said the solar flares erupted from a region on the sun that just rotated into view from the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> on Monday. The area, marked by sun spots, will take about 11 more days to move across the face of solar sphere as the sun rotates. `` The probability of there being more solar flares is high,'' said <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>. The fact that two flares occurred in the sun spot region indicates that it is very active and apt to spawn more eruptions, he said. The sun goes through phases of intense activity. It passed a low point in 1986 and is now climbing toward an expected peak in intensity later this year or early in 1990. A flare occurs when energy stored by the sun's magnetic fields suddenly becomes unstable and is converted to geomagnetic radiation within a few minutes. <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> said solar telescopes recorded the flare of as a tongue flamelike particles rising some 70,000 miles from the surface of the sun.
