<HEAD>Budget-Caused Cutbacks Will Cost Eventually, Patrick Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel Tuesday that budget-caused cutbacks in staff and computer equipment this year could cost the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> $ 48 million in future revenues. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> needs additional funds in fiscal 1990 to hire more staff and buy more computers to relieve a backlog of license and telecommunications service applications that increased about 20 percent from 1988 to 1989. `` Delays in licensing caused by staff shortages or lack of automatiion affect not only applicants, but adversely impact the -LRB- gross national product -RRB- and reduce tax revenues,'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee on commerce, justice and state, the judiciary and related agencies. The subcommittee is considering the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>'s request for $ 109.8 million in funds for the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> for fiscal 1990. That would be an increase of $ 10.2 million over the fiscal 1989 appropriation of $ 99.6 million. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had sought $ 111.9 million. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s appropriation in fiscal 1988 was the same as fiscal 1989 and that the agency began fiscal 1989 on Oct. 1, 1988, with a $ 5 million deficit because of pay raises and health benefit increases. To cover that shortage, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said he imposed a hiring freeze and did not replace workers who retired or quit. Other cuts included a 75 percent reduction in automated data processing equipment purchases, he said. He said his staff estimated that a one-year reduction of $ 5 million in its fiscal 1989 appropriation, if continued beyond fiscal 1990, could reduce the present value of federal tax revenues by roughly $ 53 million, producing a net revenue loss of about $ 48 million. Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Early </PERSON>, D-Mass., criticized the cutback in automated equipment purchases `` I do n't think that's good management,'' he told <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said the agency had gotten to the point it could n't cut staff any further He said in the first quarter of fiscal 1988 the agency had a backlog of 10,322 applications for new services in the telephone industry. By the first quarter of fiscal 1989 the backlog had grown to 12,317 applications or a 19 percent increase. The backlog in radio applications was 20 percent, he said.
