<FIRST>r w AM-Medicaid-NursingHomes     03-07 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicaid-Nursing Homes,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Backs Plan to Recover Costs from Estates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal and state governments could save as much as $ 500 million a year if efforts were made to recover some of the costs of nursing home care from the estates of Medicaid recipients and their spouses, a congressional report said Tuesday. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> recommends that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> require states to establish asset-recovery programs similar to one run by the state of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, which recovers about $ 10 for every $ 1 spent on its Medicaid program. `` If implemented carefully, estate recovery programs can achieve savings, while treating the elderly equitably and humanely,'' the report said. However, `` it's a sensitive issue whenever you talk about someone's right to leave an inheritance,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Linz </PERSON>, assistant director of <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid issues for the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Linz </LOCATION> estimated total federal and state Medicaid savings at $ 400 million to $ 500 million if all states had an estate recovery program such as <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s. Medicaid is a more than $ 50 billion federal-state health assistance program for the poor. The federal government sets broad guidelines for the programs and provides the bulk of the money, but the states set eligibilty criteria and administer the programs. Most of the elderly who become eligible for Medicaid's nursing home benefit do so by `` spending down'' their assets to meet the income and asset limits for the program, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. However, the program allows a Medicaid recipient to retain his home _ usually a person's primary asset _ as long as a family member is living there or the recipient expects to return to the home. Unless a state has an estate recovery program, however, it can not recover assets that remain at the time the recipient dies, or if their spouse is living, at the time the spouse dies, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Often, the only remaining asset is the recipient's home. Twenty-one states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> have programs allowing recovery of Medicaid benefits from recipients estates, with annual recoveries totaling about $ 42 million, according to a June report by the inspector general for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. None of the programs approaches the effectiveness of the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> program, which recovers an average of $ 327 per Medicaid nursing home resident, which totals about $ 4 million annually, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The next highest recovery rates are $ 160 per Medicaid nursing home resident in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and $ 109 in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. The key elements of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s program, according to the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, are procedures for identifying a Medicaid applicant's assets, tracking and preserving assets while Medicaid assistance is provided, and recovering from the recipient's estate. The law also allows for recovery from the spouse's estate if the state did n't recover from the recipient's estate. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said advocacy groups for the elderly in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> say that the state's program incorporates enough flexibility so that estate recoveries do n't create undue hardships on the recipient's heirs.
