<FIRST>r a AM-PhiladelphiaSlayings     03-07 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philadelphia Slayings,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>South-to-North Caravan to Renew Civil Rights Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-five years after the slayings of three young men drew the nation's attention to the civil rights movement, a new Freedom Summer caravan is being planned to commemorate the deaths, organizers said Tuesday. Civil rights leaders from <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and across the nation were joined by Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> at the announcement of the caravan, which will leave <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, on June 21 and travel to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It will be kind of a prayer pilgrimage of reconcilation where the spirit of good will which <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> has recaptured will come alive again,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, the former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equality </ORGANIZATION>. Farmer, who played a major role in the original Freedom Summer demonstrations in 1964, said <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> has shed its `` ugly image of hatred'' and can be a model for the rest of the nation. He said he realized that when he <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> greeted him in the governor's office once held by the late <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilbo </PERSON>, a strident segregationist. `` I knew then that in this great land of ours, all things are possible,'' <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> also spoke of change in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. `` Today, once more, the officials of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> are standing in the schoolhouse door, but this time we are standing in that door to open it wider and to make sure that everybody gets in,'' he said. The caravan will commemorate the slayings of <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>, whose bodies were found in an earthen dam near <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> six weeks after their deaths on June 21, 1964. <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> was a 21-year-old black from <ORGANIZATION> Meridian </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, 20, and <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>, 24, were white New Yorkers who were among the young people from around the nation who flocked to the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> to protest racial discrimination during Freedom Summer. <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> <PERSON> Moss </PERSON>, the sister of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, said the caravan would `` recreate that moment in time in 1964 to educate the youth and re-educate those older of us who maybe have become complacent in our lives, and to re-dedicate ourselves to human rights, civil rights and voter registration.'' State Rep. <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> branch of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, said the caravan would begin with rallies in <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Meridian </ORGANIZATION> and then head on to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. Later stops are planned in <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where a rally will be held on June 24 near where <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> is buried. <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> vanished after being arrested and jailed in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> on a traffic violation. No one was tried for murder, but eight men were convicted on federal charges of denying the three their civil rights. The incident was fictionalized in the Oscar-nominated movie `` Mississippi Burning,'' which has won critical acclaim but also has been widely accused of minimizing the role of black Mississippians.
