<HEAD>Pickering Confirmed U.N. Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 99-0 on Tuesday to confirm career diplomat <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> to be <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON>, who will succeed retired Army Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, most recently served as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. During his 30-year career as a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officer he also has been ambassador to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. No opposition to the nomination was voiced during a brief debate on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor, and senators of both parties hailed <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> as an experienced and talented diplomat. Several said that he begins his duties at the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> with opportunities for breakthroughs in settling conflicts in many parts of the world. Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, the senior <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> will confront anti-American, anti-Israeli and pro-Soviet attitudes from many <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> members. `` He is wading into a real quagmire ... of anti-American and pro-communist bias,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. In the roll call, only Sen. <PERSON> Quentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Burdick </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, did not vote. No mention was made in the brief <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate of the controversy that developed when, during his service as ambassador to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> accepted a private document from a Central American official and delivered it to <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, then a staff member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The document _ apparently later delivered by <PERSON> North </PERSON> to leaders of the Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> _ was an offer to provide $ 1 million in military equipment. During his confirmation hearing <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said that although he delivered the letter to <PERSON> North </PERSON>, he did not believe he had violated a congressional ban in effect at the time which barred direct or indirect aid to the Contras. He said he delivered the letter to North outside of normal <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> channels only because he knew <PERSON> North </PERSON> was the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's liaison with the Contras.
