<HEAD>Walesa Says Talks Clear Obstacles, Accord Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government and the opposition have overcome barriers to a compromise, and an accord on political and social reforms should be signed April 3, <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` I am very satisfied,'' the founder of Solidarity said after an eight-hour meeting with the interior minister, Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, and other government and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials. Opposition spokesmen said agreement was reached on legalizing the banned <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, known by its initials <ORGANIZATION> NZS </ORGANIZATION>, which had become a sticking point in the month-old `` round table'' negotiations. The news came on the eve of the anniversary of student riots March 8, 1968. On Tuesday, city officials in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> took the unusual step of issuing permits for two commemorative marches by students. `` We are finalizing the round table,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. `` All basic problems, like -LRB- union -RRB- pluralism ... will be achieved in time, in line with our commitments.'' Authorities proposed negotiations with the opposition, led by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s union, because of strikes in 1988 and fears of further social problems due to shortages, low wages and inflation running at an annual rate of about 60 percent. Among the goals <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and other opposition leaders set were restoration of legal status to Solidarity, the independent farmers' union Rural Solidarity and the student association All were formed in the labor turmoil of 1980, when Solidarity became the first free union in the Soviet bloc. They were outlawed after martial law was imposed in December 1981 but have continued to function. Officials indicated soon after the talks began Feb. 6 that Solidarity and Rural Solidarity would be legalized, but the student group's fate remained in doubt. A joint communique carried by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> after Tuesday's meeting said `` there were conditions for a further rapprochement of stances on the key issues of dialogue and directions of proposed political, economic and social reforms, including the registration of the <ORGANIZATION> NZS </ORGANIZATION> student union.'' <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Konopka </PERSON>, a Solicarity spokesman, said: `` It seems that this is an unequivocal decision on registration of <ORGANIZATION> NZS </ORGANIZATION>. This is good news for the students, but it's also good news for us because all the people taking part in the talks on our side have emphasized that registering <ORGANIZATION> NZS </ORGANIZATION> was one of the key problems.'' No other agreements were mentioned in the joint statement. It also said nothing of such issues as the form for parliamentary elections in which the opposition would participate and an opposition demand that wages be indexed to the cost of living. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> might have to meet again but the working groups on specific topics should finish by March 20. The period between then and April 3 would allow each side to study the tentative agreement, he said. About his meeting with <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, who leads the government delegation, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said: `` We are removing obstacles that have appeared here and there, but we are only removing them politically and the rest must be worked out at the tables because the experts are there.'' <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON>, national spokesman for Solidarity, said: `` I imagine the final agreement will be in the form of a resolution including general declarations, maybe accompanied by annexes with details, signed by all the participants at the round table.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> spoke to reporters outside the Roman Catholic episcopate in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> after returning from the meeting accompanied by advisers. He boarded a train soon afterward for <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> port where he works as a shipyard electrician and founded Solidarity during a strike in August 1980. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Walesa-Kiszczak </LOCATION> meeting included `` attempts to separate out subjects on which we can reach agreement in order to leave for the future subjects on which we have n't reached agreement.'' At a news conference, he listed requirements for an accord as `` working out a document about what links Poles, an agreement on non-confrontational elections and practical implementation of trade union pluralism.''
