<HEAD>Subcommittee Approves Uniform Poll Closing Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee approved legislation Tuesday to impose a uniform closing time for polls across the 48 contiguous states. The elections subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved the measure on a voice vote. Rep. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>, D-Wash. and the subcommittee chairman, said he expected <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will approve the bill this year The measure, similar to ones twice approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, now goes to the full committee. Election officials in the West have complained that voters in their states sometimes decide not to vote when the winner of a presidential election is known before their polls close and that the drop in turnout has affected the outcome of close local races. Under the bill, polls would close simultaneously in the 48 contiguous states at 9 p.m. EST. In the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zone </ORGANIZATION>, daylight saving time would be extended for a maxiumum of two weeks in presidential election years. The extension would allow polls in that time zone to close at 7 p.m. PDT. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> are exempt from the legislation. <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said the need for a uniform poll closing time became apparent after the 1980 and 1984 presidential elections when the television networks, using exit polling data, projected the winners before western polls closed. In 1988, however, the problem was different as President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> rolled up a `` large electoral college majority'' before western polls closed, said <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>. `` Had this legislation been in place, all of the polls would have been closed before a winner was known,'' said <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>. <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said that studies have shown voter turnout can drop by up to 2 percent when a winner in the presidential contest is known before the polls close. `` This can be a crucial in tight, local elections,'' said <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>.
