<HEAD>Rostenkowski Says Major Deficit Reduction Would Mean Tax Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget director on Tuesday that any major reduction in the federal deficit would require a tax increase. `` I do n't want to raise taxes, but I ca n't see how we can achieve a significant amount of deficit reduction on the spending side only,'' <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said as his committee heard testimony from <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> also told <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> that there was little chance of enacting two administration tax-increasing proposals, broadening the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> tax to all state and local employees and blocking an automatic reduction in the airport excise tax. Those `` simply do not have the votes to pass,'' he said. The White House refuses to consider those levies as tax boosts. In response to questions by the committee, <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said he might consider other revenue-raising measures as something other than tax increases. For example, applying the telephone excise tax to wire services, now exempt, might be considered `` loophole closing,'' he said. Other changes might be considered user fees. But he said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had shown no indication that he was softening his opposition to new taxes. `` If someone were going to change his -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s -RRB- mind, it would take a major effort,'' he said. At a hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D-La., complained to Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> that the administration was using rosy economic assumptions and other gimmicks to make its budget proposal fall within the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction targets <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said the administration had n't offered a realistic plan that could serve as `` a starting point'' for serious negotiations and that the Gramm-Rudman targets might have to be relaxed even if a credible plan were advanced. He said it was doubtful that `` enough taxes and real budget cuts with real economic assumptions'' could be enacted to meet the Gramm-Rudman targets for fiscal 1990. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> defended the administration's economic assumptions as realistic and said that while Gramm-Rudman was imperfect, `` it is a form of sanity'' that has been reassuring to financial markets anxious to see progress toward deficit-reduction. Like <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said he would oppose changing the Gramm-Rudman law and its $ 100 billion deficit limit for fiscal 1990. The administration claims it has met the target without increasing taxes. `` I feel very strongly that we should not move the goal lines,'' he said. `` ... I think we do have a starting point. I have optimism that we're going to reach the goal line without moving it.'' <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan to resume discussions this week with congressional budget writers. The administration's goal is full-scale negotiations on the budget for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1. Congressional Democrats complained that the administration has been slow to provide information on policies it would favor in a deficit-reduction plan, especially the cuts required in domestic programs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a news conference Tuesday, repeated his assertion that he has provided <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> with more detail than other presidents did at the beginning of their administrations. `` More detail has been sent to the hill at this time in our administration _ let me clarify that _ than at any time for either the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, 1981, or the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration in'77,'' he said. `` They had n't gone up with near this amount of detail to the hill.''
