<HEAD>U.N. Official Calls For `Month of Tranquillity' in Sudan War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official on Tuesday called for a month of peace in the war-torn south to enable the transport of 100,000 tons of food and medicine to about 2 million people facing starvation this summer. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, director general of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund and personal representative of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, said the international community was in a race against time to position and distribute the supplies in the south before the rainy season starts in May. The operation will cost an estimated $ 20 million for food that has not yet arrived in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, $ 48 million for transportation and about $ 12 million for other expenses in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON>, executive director for the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>. He said this amount does not include the worth of the bulk of the food already in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, nor money for medication or immunization programs or vital structures like digging wells. `` This is a race against time _ a race to avoid the repetition of the disaster which happened when the rains blocked the transportation of foodstuff,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. He said more than 250,000 people died last year when food was blocked, up to one-half of them children. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said 2.25 million southerners in government - and rebel-held areas needed food and medication in varying degrees this summer and that 100,000 people could die if the operation failed He spoke on the eve of a U.N.-organized conference in which Western donor governments, non-governmental relief agencies and the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> governments are participating to organize the ambitious rescue operation. The rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is not representated. <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> described the operation as `` very very daunting'' and stressed there was an `` absolute need'' for a month of peace. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said he had indications the rebels might agree to such a proposal. `` We are in some consultation with them. I believe the prospects of developing a month of tranquillity is something which can emerge in the next few day,'' he said. Sources close to the conference said the donors, especially the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, would strongly pressure the <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> government to enter peace talks with the rebels. On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> urged Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s government to talk peace. The Sudanese government and the rebels both have used food as a weapon in the 6-year-old war in the south. Western relief officials estimate that in 1988 alone, about 560,000 southerners died of starvation or while fleeing the war. The rainy season starts in May and lasts until the end of September. It turns roads into swamps and makes airstrips unusable. Referring to previous international efforts to bring relief to the south, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said they were `` far too short to carry people through, once the rains start in the spring.'' <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> said that starting Wednesday, a six-week program would begin to transport 3,000 tons of food and supplies to the south in <LOCATION> Hercules </LOCATION> C-130s.
