<HEAD>Human Rights Group Asks Jamaica To Halt Executions</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 8 p.m. EST - time set by source.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> urged <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> on Wednesday to abolish its death penalty and allow its 200 prisoners on death row to live, saying many may not have had a fair trial. The London-based human rights group, which opposes the death penalty unconditionally, said many of the prisoners are poor and illiterate and were not well represented in court. Some have been convicted by a single witness's testimony and have difficulties making appeals, it said in its 85-page report. <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s death row population is one of the highest per capita in the world. The <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indies </LOCATION> island nation has about 2.3 million people. The death penalty, which was halted for four years ending in 1981, is mandatory for murder in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, said Amnesty. It said authorities hanged 59 people between August 1980 and February 1988. Amnesty's report covered conditions from 1984 to 1988. It said nearly half of those sentenced to death have spent more than five years on death row, and some have been there for 12 years. They are kept in the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catherine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> outside the capital <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, where they live in unsanitary conditions, without opportunities to exercise or work, the report said.
