<HEAD>D.C. Council Votes for Five-Year Jail Term for Criminals with Guns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, taking emergency action in an attempt to curb drug-related violence in the nation's capital, voted Tuesday to require that people who use guns when they commit a crime in the city must be sentenced to five years in prison. It approved a bill also aimed at improving the city's before-trial detention program by allowing judges to refuse to permit bond for people accused of violent crimes even if they have no criminal record `` This is an emergency bill, and requires a lot of debate, but these are emergency times,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathanson </PERSON>, a member of the council. `` The people of this city are telling us we have to do something.'' The emergency measure, which will remain in effect for 90 days before being reviewed, came as the city sought to slow the pace of drug-related killings. Police blame about 60 percent of last year's record 372 killings on drugs So far this year, 98 people have been slain in the district, 43 more than during the matching period in 1988. The legislation also attempts to stem a flow of illegally purchased weapons into the nation's capital. According to police statistics, 3,863 weapons were seized on city streets during 1988, compared with 2,225 the year before. The bill survived a challenge from several council members who complained that it would clog the city's already overcrowded court and prison systems, and objections from others who said it needed more debate. Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> proposed the measure almost two weeks ago, saying the city should start `` an all-out assault on weapons.'' Since then, city, police and court officials have twice met to discuss the bill. The emergency measure strengthens the city's handgun law, already considered one of the toughest in the nation. The old law set maximum punishment at one year in jail and a $ 1,000 fine for anyone caught with unregistered weapons.
