<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From the Cathedral of <LOCATION> Chartres </LOCATION>' soaring Gothic vaults to <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>'s weightless <PERSON> Desmoiselles </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Avignon </PERSON>, works of art have long been associated with flight. Now, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> artist <PERSON> Lowry </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON>' sculpture `` Boundless Aperture'' is scheduled to take off with the space shuttle Discovery and give art a lift, quite literally, out of this world. The 7-pound cubic sculpture, part of the artist's 20-year effort to stretch the human imagination, is the nation's first and possibly last interstellar art offering. `` If any art went up previously it was done without our knowledge and we certainly do n't approve of it,'' said <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Maull </PERSON>, who was staff director for the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> committee that approved <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON>'s work for flight. `` And there is no intention to send any other objects up at this time.'' <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON> conceived his `` Boundless Aperture'' sculpture more than two decades ago as part of a larger project entitled `` The Quiet Axis,'' that includes one sculpture embedded in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> floor off <LOCATION> Easter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and another placed in the <LOCATION> Hindu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kush </LOCATION> mountains in central <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` Boundless Aperture'' consists of a 6-inch cube inside of which floats another cube bearing colorful holographic plates inscribed with poetry. On its return it will be placed inside a rock outcropping on the DeCordova Museum's grounds in <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The artist allows that his latest sculpture is fairly esoteric, but insists that anyone can appreciate space art. `` There are more art enthusiasts out there than the people at the museums,'' he said. `` A lot of people are very eager to see a cultural dimension to the space effort. It's humanizing.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Big <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> is losing his marbles. Big <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> is the 80-story, marble-sheathed headquarters of <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, nicknamed back when the company was known as <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. At 1,136 feet, it is the tallest marble-faced building in the world. But not for long. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> officials say Big <PERSON> Stan </PERSON>'s 43,000 marble panels are coming loose and must go. The panels will be replaced with granite during a facelift that begins next month and could cost up to $ 80 million before its completion in three years, said <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, manager of engineering for <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>. `` We decided to bite the bullet rather than continue forever on a maintenance program,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said Monday of the replacement project. `` We decided to get it over with.'' Many <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> artists and architects are ready for the change. `` Carrara marble, which is what's on the building, is beautiful,'' says architect <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Netsch </PERSON>. `` Michelangelo used it. But <PERSON> Michelangelo </PERSON> did n't leave his work outside.'' The used marble is too weak for buildings and too warped for countertops. Until a buyer is found, the marble will be piled up outside the headquarters, said <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. `` This granite is very strong and stable,'' he said. `` I wanted to make sure that 15 years from now someone does n't have to go through what I'm going through.''
</TEXT>
