<HEAD>Thornburgh Gives Conditions for Using US Soldiers in Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers will be used against the narcotics trade in drug-producing nations only in support roles and at the request of those countries, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> commented near the end of a visit to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> during which he met with government officials, including President <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Estenssoro </PERSON>, and addressed a conference on drug abuse. `` It is important to reaffirm this administration's position with regard to the use of military forces outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he told a news conference. `` These forces will never be mobilized except at the request of the host country and only in ways that would provide logistical and law enforcement support to these countries.'' About 50 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, border patrol, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and military training and advisory personnel now are assigned to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> in those capacities. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sent 195 soldiers to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> for three months in 1986 to provide logistical support for raids on labs that process coca leaves, the basis of cocaine. Since the soldiers left, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has increased its support to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s anti-drug campaign, training and equipping 600 narcotics police permanently assigned to coca-producing regions. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> is visiting <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to meet with leaders about how to stem the flow of drugs. Traveling with