at doing so will adversely affect their careers, and that there still is no system to alert instructors to students with a history of problems. `` The bottom line,'' <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> said, `` is that <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> instructors still are not trained to conduct high-risk training and that students still are not screened to make sure they can handle the dangers.'' In <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s case, <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> pointed to <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> findings that he had untrained and unsupervised instructors and was prevented from dropping out because of pressure on the school to increase the number of graduates it turned out. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> also faulted the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> for its investigation of <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s death and said the service does n't always investigate such deaths as thoroughly as it should In addition, the investigators wrote that `` the ability of these investigations as presently conducted to identify and address safety issues is questionable.''
