 Prosecutors on Wednesday arrested a former vice labor minister on charges of bribery in connection with a widening stock-profiteering scandal involving top government leaders. <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kato </PERSON>, 58, became the highest-ranking public official to be arrested in the unfolding scandal after <PERSON> Shigeru </PERSON> <PERSON> Kano </PERSON>, former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s employment service division, who was taken in Feb. 17. Also Wednesday, <PERSON> Masao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tatsumi </PERSON>, former executive of <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an employment-information conglomerate, was apprehended by prosecutors on charges of bribing <PERSON> Kato </PERSON>. That brought to 11 the total number of scandal-related arrests to date. Two Recruit officials who were arrested Feb. 15 were freed Tuesday by the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> District Prosecutor's Office. The office has yet to decide whether they will be indicted. Recruit is at the center of the scandal in which a select number of individuals, particularly politicians, were offered the opportunity to purchase bargain-priced shares of a real estate subsidiary up until September 1986. When the shares were offered for over-the-counter trading in October 1986, their value rose substantially and holders were able to earn hefty profits. <PERSON> Kato </PERSON>'s arrest had been expected for weeks. Prosecutors had been questioning him over the past few days over his ties to Recruit. <PERSON> Kato </PERSON> allegedly purchased 3,000 unlisted shares in a <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary in September 1986 and earned a windfall of about $ 53,000 a month later, <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> quoted prosecutors as saying. The former vice labor minister, who retired voluntarily in January 1988, has been accused of providing special favors to Recruit during his 1983-85 tenure as director general of the ministry's <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> said. On Monday, <PERSON> Higashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinto </PERSON>, former head of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest corporation, <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION>, was arrested on charges of accepting bribes from Recruit. The Recruit scandal has severely damaged the reputation of Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, whose support rating has dwindled to 21.3 percent in the latest poll by the mass circulation daily <ORGANIZATION> Yomiuri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Three </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers resigned after reports that they directly or indirectly purchased Recruit stock. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> has denied personal involvement in the scandal but has acknowledged his own aide bought 2,000 shares of Recruit stock.
