<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, March 8, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Wonderful Dogs' on National Geographic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's probably the first time during the course of an interview that the star has been told, `` Get out of the trash!'' No, the star is not <PERSON> Geraldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON>. She is Cinnamon, a red Doberman pinscher, a rescue dog whose job it is to search through forests, lakes or earthquake rubble to find people. `` The only thing Cinnamon loves more than people is doughnuts,'' notes Cinnamon's owner and trainer, <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, explaining why Cinnamon keeps dipping her nose into the conference room trash can seeking the discarded remains of a pastry. Cinnamon is one of the dogs taken to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to help find victims buried beneath the massive 1985 earthquake. And she is among the remarkable working dogs featured in the National Geographic special, `` Those Wonderful Dogs,'' airing tonight on PBS. `` Those Wonderful Dogs'' is a fascinating and lovingly photographed film that will please dog-lovers enormously but does n't get overly sentimental It was written and produced by <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Jampel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiley </PERSON> provides the narration. The special is dedicated to the memory of film editor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON>, who did such an excellent job of putting it all together. Other dogs featured in the special include sheepdogs, combat dogs, dogs who assist the disabled and sled dogs. The special ranged as far as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> to observe a team of 10 sheepdogs who help one couple manage a huge, remote sheep farm. `` Without the dogs,'' says farmer <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Calder </PERSON>, `` we'd be broke in 12 months.'' He observes that his dogs are willing to work till they drop, and all they seek in return is approval from their master. There are two different kinds of sheepdogs, the ones who nip at the heels of the sheep and `` headers,'' who control the sheep from in front by staring into their eyes. Once the sheep are in the pens, the dogs run across the backs of the packed herd to move them along. The special moves on to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON> takes the filmmakers through the training regimen that has produced her champion sled teams, regular winners of the 1,100-mile Iditarod sled race. One of the most touching segments is set in a more mundane environment, a typical <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> home, where lives 17-year-old <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Knowlton </PERSON>, a victim of spina bifida who uses a wheelchair, and his yellow Labrador retriever, Zest. Zest is a product of California-based Canine Companions for Independence. Similar to a Seeing Eye dog, she helps her owner by pulling his wheelchair, turning off light switches, picking up dropped objects _ and serving as an ice-breaker. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> says he used to be too shy to approach other students at his school, but now they come up to him to pet the dog. If you grew up on `` Lassie,'' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> will disappoint you when she insists that rescue dogs like Cinnamon are n't aware that they are saving people's lives, but are only playing a hide-and-seek game. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> is a founder of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dogs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, whose members found dozens of survivors beneath the rubble of the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> earthquake. Cinnamon herself was responsible for finding eight people, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> says. Cinnamon also searches for people who have wandered into wilderness areas and become lost. She even locates drowning victims, riding in a boat and detecting the gases emitted by a body beneath the water. Maybe Cinnamon does n't know she's saving lives, but she does have a different signal when she finds a live person _ `` she wags her behind'' _ than the more subdued scratching at the surface when she finds a dead person. Rescue dogs have to be trained to ignore their natural instinct to jump off unstable surfaces. They are taught to walk a horizontal ladder so they become more aware of the position of their hind feet. Rescue dogs are selected for their love of all people. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said many dogs will search all day for their beloved owner, but do n't care about strangers. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said she picked Cinnamon, now 8 -LCB-, out of litter of pups because she was the one most eager for human contact. Sure enough, though she had only just met her `` interviewer,'' she happily administered a face-washing.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: YOUR MOTHER WEARS COMBAT BOOTS _ <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> hopes these are not fighting words, simply the title of a new comedy movie to air later this season. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Eden </PERSON> stars as an overly protective mother who follows her son into airborne training with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. It was filmed in part at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Infantry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Benning </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga </LOCATION>.
