<SECOND>BC-No Children, Adv 12,1220</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Landmark Housing Measure Spurs Debate, Bodes Wide-ranging Effects</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note that law goes into effect Sunday, March 12.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Housing discrimination against families with children is illegal starting Sunday, but no-kids communities are fighting to protect their lifestyles even as experts laud the new law for addressing a national crisis. `` There will be resistance -LRB- and -RRB- claims of reverse discrimination, but the fact of the matter is <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has decided families with children have a great need for housing and this law is designed to help them,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>, staff attorney for the San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION>. A 1980 <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> study found that 75 percent of rental units nationwide banned or restricted children. Other surveys found 90 percent of apartment complexes in some communities closed to children. `` We just found an epidemic of discrimination against families with children all over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It was really tragic,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., a co-sponsor of the Fair Housing Amendments Act of 1988 signed into law by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in September The act bans discrimination against families with children, with some exemptions, and adds the handicapped to housing law prohibiting discrimination on the basis of sex, religion, national origin, color and race. `` Blatant and legal cases of discrimination against families with children ... -LRB- are -RRB- happening all over the country and in all types of communities,'' said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Mihaly </PERSON> of the Washington-based Children's Defense Fund. _ In <LOCATION> Zephyrhills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Elmer </PERSON> were forced in January to evict their 14-year-old daughter <PERSON> Staci </PERSON> rather than go to jail for contempt of court in a dispute over deed restrictions She can visit their mobile home in a subdivision of 17 families north of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, but must live with a married brother until she turns 15 next month. Pets are allowed, but not children under 15. `` I'm not surprised. The Constitution is n't made for kids,'' <PERSON> Staci </PERSON> said. _ In <LOCATION> Margate </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Swartz </PERSON>, 9, was threatened with eviction when she moved in with her father and stepmother after her mother died After months of uncertainty, <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON> got a reprieve in January when the condominium board decided not to take action while the new federal housing act was researched. _ A <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, couple were forced to send their 3-year-old son to live with friends because of a dispute with neighbors at apartments that had been converted into condominiums with a no-children rule `` Of course we could n't just banish him into a black hole'' and he returned for clothes and toys, said his mother, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Benyahich </PERSON>. After neighbors saw him she got a call from the board's lawyer, who said if he came again `` for any reason they were going to send the sheriff out to remove him.'' _ In <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, a judge mediated an agreement allowing 46-year-old <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> to be a guest for 60 days in the condo she and her husband <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON>, 60, bought at the <ORGANIZATION> Rossmoor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Condominiums </ORGANIZATION> The condo association had not allowed the couple, who live in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, to buy property because Mrs. <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> was n't 48. The judge's Sept. 15 agreement allowed them to buy the weekend home The new housing rules allow age restrictions in retirement communities if all residents are over 62, or if at least 80 percent of the households have at least one member over 55 and special services are offered for older people, or in housing sponsored by state and federal programs for the elderly. Under a transition provision, those who are under the minimum age and were living in an elderly development as of Sept. 13, 1988, will not have to give up their residence nor will the community jeapordize its exemption. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> defends the child-free lifestyle he enjoys at a <LOCATION> Margate </LOCATION> condominium that is changing its documents to remain exempt. His sentiments are widely shared, especially among mostly elderly developments. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Oriole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gardens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Condominium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said many of his neighbors are infirm and under nurses' care, and besides, `` No one would like to have a squirrely kid next door crying in the middle of the night. `` This is our lifestyle. I'm satisfied with what we have now.'' While retirement communities are essentially exempted, adults-only developments around the country will be affected by the act. Attorney <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Poliakoff </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> contends the act encourages discrimination against the 18 - to 55-year-olds who live in adult communities, and probably wo n't open much existing housing to children <PERSON> Poliakoff </PERSON>, whose firm represents 1,700 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> communities, says most of those affected have smaller units, recreational facilities designed for adults and a surrounding social infrastructure that's not oriented to families Mobile home parks also present a special situation. `` The people who make up our membership are not elderly in the usual sense. They're active retirees, social and do n't want to live next door to children,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeowners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Conture </PERSON>. Some may have to under the new law. Mobile-home-park owners and apartment managers now face having to make developments kid-friendly with playgrounds and safety fences or figure out if they qualify for exemption as retirement havens. In areas with age restrictions, reaction to the act has been mixed, but some people are clearly upset they may have to give up adult-only living. `` We do n't think that you can just take a whole neighborhood and say we do n't want to live with children,'' said <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. `` Children have rights too.'' Sixteen states have barred housing discrimination on the basis of familial status, but experts say the laws are generally weak and contain huge loopholes. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 prohibited discrimination against families with children in apartment rentals and later extended that to condos. Mobile home parks have been exempt, a provision the federal law will override. But families still face subtler discrimination, such as limits on the number of occupants, complexes with segregated areas for adults and families with children, and other restrictive rules, said <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>. About a third of the housing complaints received by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s Department of Fair Employment and Housing involve children, he said. Enforcement of the 1988 act will rest with the states, if their housing law is substantially equivalent to federal law and enforcement mechanisms already in place are recertified by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. The federal housing agency will handle cases in those states that are n't equipped to deal with housing complaints The period to file a complaint has been extended from 180 days to a year, and an administrative law judge will now be able to hear a case and award actual damages, injunctive relief or top civil penalties of $ 50,000. At the federal court level, a $ 100,000 cap on punitive damages has been eliminated. And the federal government, previously only able to seek injunctive relief, will be able to seek civil penalties up to $ 100,000 against violators. `` Everybody needs to be educated about what the law says,'' said <PERSON> Mihaly </PERSON>. `` I think we'll begin to see fairly dramatic changes.''
</TEXT>
