 <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, which reported $ 6 billion in 1987 revenue That is exactly what Time Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> had in mind as he and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> discussed a merger over the past two years. `` We believe that by the mid-1990s the media and entertainment industry will be composed of a limited number of global giants,'' <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> told securities analysts last November. `` Time intends to be one of these companies.'' Who are the others? Mainly foreign publishing and broadcasting giants such <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and electronics behemoth <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, that have scooped up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> media concerns in a torrent of deals made possible over the past several years by their own riches and the weak <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. In his speech to analysts, <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said the spurt of acquisitions, mergers and join ventures among media companies in recent years has given these businesses `` the sheer size required to compete efficiently on a global basis.'' For example, <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said in an interview, his company's deal with <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> would give <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> better access to foreign markets for its video business. He predicted the greatest impact of the deal would come in <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> overseas operations. Analysts said they expected foreigners to continue buying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies. <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION>, noted that <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> _ which bought <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> last year _ has expressed interest in owning a motion picture company, including <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Bertelsmann </ORGANIZATION> is not as well known in this country as some other big media names, such as <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> or <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, but it owns the publisher <ORGANIZATION> Doubleday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and RCA records. <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON> suggested <ORGANIZATION> Bertelsmann </ORGANIZATION> might also move into the film business. <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> owns newspaper, magazine and book publishing operations in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. His American holdings include <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the publisher of <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guide </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Row </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>; 20th <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> has no plans to slow down although <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which had $ 4.3 billion in 1988 revenue, has become burdened by debt because of its many acquisitions. <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> also plans to raise $ 1 billion or more for buying other communications companies around the world. London-based <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> had $ 2.6 billion in revenue in 1987. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> _ motivated partly by a rivalry with <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> _ wants to see that figure swell to $ 5 billion to $ 9 billion, and he has said he intends to keep acquiring businesses until he reaches that goal. Last year he won a long battle for <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and also agreed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Official Airline Guides. American companies expect to join the consolidation. <PERSON> Francine </PERSON> <PERSON> Blum </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Wertheim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schroder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western and <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> are candidates for consolidations among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms. She also said she expected to see alliances between movie studios and the major television networks.
