<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices bounced back on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> today after a plunge in early trading, while the dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which shed 9.63 points Monday, rose 61.08 points, or 0.19 percent, today to close at 31,937.94. After a drop in early trading, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> started upward at midmorning. The index's early decline followed news that <PERSON> Hisashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinto </PERSON>, former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest company, and his former secretary were arrested Monday on bribery charges in connection with a major stock scandal involving top politicians, dealers said. `` But the Nikkei started to recover from its setback following Finance Minister -LRB- <PERSON> Tatsuo </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Murayama </PERSON>'s comment that the yen's weak performance had nothing to do with the stock scandal,'' said <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishizuka </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Murayama </PERSON> told reporters today that the yen's decline `` did not have anything to do -LRB- with Shinto's arrest -RRB- ... It's a market after all, and who knows why it moves.'' <PERSON> Ishizuka </PERSON> said investors' interest in steel and construction issues contributed to the index's rise. Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1 billion shares. In currency dealings, the dollar finished at 129.03 yen, up 1.40 yen from Monday's 127.63-yen close. The currency started opened at 129.25 yen and ranged between 128.87 yen and 129.28 yen. After gaining 2.12 yen over four days last week, the dollar had declined by 0.49 yen on Monday. Dealers attributed the dollar's higher opening in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today to its gains on overseas markets overnight. But the rate did not move much once trading started in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Minori </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeuchi </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` Hardly anybody was participating in the afternoon session after failing to lead the market anywhere, because buying and selling were equally mixed,'' she said. Only speculative investors were trading, adjusting their dollar positions, Ms. <PERSON> Takeuchi </PERSON> added.
