<HEAD>Signup Period Set for Conservation Reserve Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers will have another opportunity this summer to put highly erodible land in the government's Conservation Reserve Program, says Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said Monday the ninth CRP signup period will be July 17 through Aug. 4 and that farmers who want to offer land under the program should contact local offices of the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Under the program, farmers agree to take land from production for 10 years. In return, based on bids they submit, farmers who are accepted receive annual rental payments from the government and one-time assistance to pay half the cost of planting trees, shrubs and grass to guard against erosion. The eighth round of applications was completed on Feb. 24, but <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said the final results will not be ready until June. Meanwhile, he said, the `` maximum acceptable rental rates'' for land offered by farmers will be the same as in the seventh signup. Those are the maximum payments under the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> for land put into the program. The rates vary by state and often within single states themselves, from a maximum of $ 30 per acre annually for less-productive land to as much as $ 115 per acre each year for better land. A total of 28.2 million acres was accepted into <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> through the first seven signups, with the annual payment averaging around $ 49 per acre. The goal of the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> as set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the 1985 farm law is to have 40 million to 45 million acres of highly erodible cropland taken from production by the end of 1990.
