<HEAD>Rockwell Fined $5.5 Million for Defense Procurement Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been fined $ 5.5 million for double-billing the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, and the punishment will serve as a warning to other defense contractors, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> says. `` We're quite pleased, and we hope that a fine of that magnitude will send out a message to the defense industry that the federal courts are taking defense procurement fraud very seriously,'' <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Consuelo </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> on Monday fined the aerospace giant for overbilling the Pentagon for a navigation satellite system. The judge also ordered <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> to pay restitution of $ 446,248 and placed the company on probation for five years. <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON> had pleaded guilty to conspiracy and contempt of court but maintained that two high-level employees, not the company, were responsible for the overcharges and a subsequent coverup. The company said it would appeal the fine. The El Segundo-based company was fined for conspiring with some of its managers to overbill the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> by nearly $ 500,000 on the $ 1.2 billion NAVSTAR navigation satellite system between 1982 and 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement reiterating its contention that the overbilling was the responsibility of renegade employees acting in what they perceived to be the company's benefit. `` <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON> was sentenced today because of our responsibility under the law for the acts of our employees,'' it said. `` We accept that responsibility but we continue to believe that the company itself should not have been indicted.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> manager, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavodnik </PERSON>, 47, has pleaded guilty to lying to the government and conspiracy in the case. He was sentenced last month to a year of probation. His supervisor, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, 60, was acquitted of the charges by a federal jury. The largest fine imposed on a defense contractor was $ 115 million in 1988 against <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, manufacturer of electronic, mechanical and hydraulic systems for aircraft, was fined for its guilty plea to four counts of defrauding the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> by overbilling on aircraft parts. The company admitted it had billed the department for things like babysitting, country clubs and servants for its executives.
