<HEAD>Quayle Backs Satellite Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has come up with enough government money to keep the Landsat earth-watching satellites operating at least until a review of the program can be completed, his spokesman says. The earth-sensing satellites were due to be turned off March 31, when the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> would run out of money to keep them going. <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> needed $ 9.4 million to operate the satellites until the fiscal year ends on Sept. 30. But emergency funding will come from departments that use Landsat images _ State, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> _ as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>. Landsats scan the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> with seven kinds of instruments, giving detailed images of the land and vegetation. <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON> said a review is being made of the satellite system. `` The plug wo n't be pulled before the review is completed,'' <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON> said. `` The review will be completed prior to -LRB- congressional -RRB- oversight of the FY 1990 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> budget.'' A House Science, Space and Technology subcommittee was conducting a hearing this afternoon on the Landsat. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is the new chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which studies the national space programs. <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON> said he did not know how much money would be necessary to keep the system operating until the end of the fiscal year, but `` it could be less -LRB- than $ 9.4 million -RRB- if we can implement some cost economies.'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration proposed no money for the current and future fiscal years, but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> restored enough to keep the satellites operating until the end of the month. The <ORGANIZATION> Earth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, known as EOSAT, currently operates two satellites, <ORGANIZATION> Landsats </ORGANIZATION> 4 and 5, which provide photos for mineral exploration, checking soil conditions and vegetation, urban and rural planning, monitoring volcanoes and tracing ocean currents. Both satellites are well past their expected lifetimes and are not fully operational, but they are providing useful information. An improved satellite, Landsat 6, is under construction. That project will continue because money was provided to complete and launch that satellite.
