<SECOND>PM-Accused Banker,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Bank Chairman Free To Return To Banking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Stanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> is free to re-enter the banking business under a federal appeals court opinion lifting a ban by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> The decision was a victory for the 58-year-old <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> banker in his four-year struggle to fight civil charges that he misused bank funds. `` This should have ended four years ago. ... It should never have started,'' <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> said Monday. `` I think my honesty ranks with that of any officer who has ever served a bank in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. I am guilty of mistakes in judgement, but I am not guilty of dishonesty.'' An attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the opinion overturning its ban on <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> would hinder efforts to clean up abuses in banking. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in January 1988 removed <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> from his position as officer and director of the Detroit-area bank-holding company and forbade him from engaging in future banking activities. <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON>, however, had resigned in July 1984 from his position as the head of the bank his father founded. He left the banking company nearly a year before the comptroller of the currency began proceedings to remove him in an investigation of misuse of bank funds. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATIO