<HEAD>Apple Unveils Macintosh IIcx And New Monitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, hoping to get back on track after recent pricing blunders and a projected drop in earnings this quarter, is unveiling a more compact but equally powerful Macintosh computer and two large, extra-sharp monitors. The Macintosh IIcx was scheduled to make its debut today in a glitzy teleconference broadcast from a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> hotel to customers, resellers, reporters and analysts in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hannover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The Macintosh IIcx, the third member of the Macintosh family announced in the last six months, features the <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> 68030 and 68882 microprocessors, takes up less desk space than the earlier II and IIx models and can be serviced and reconfigured more easily. `` I think the IIcx is a product that should have been in the marketplace sooner,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lupatkin </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Hambrecht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` It's probably the most appealing offering in the Mac family and should do well.'' He said sales of the Macintosh IIcx should begin making an impact on <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings in the next quarter, since the company is set to ship the computers immediately. <PERSON> Lupatkin </PERSON> had some reservations about the new computer's price. `` The product is priced a little bit expensively,'' he said. `` But I think it would have sported a much higher price had Apple not had the difficulty it had'' when the company raised prices last fall in response to a memory chip shortage. The result of that price hike was a sharp drop in Mac II sales that is expected to hurt the company this quarter. Apple said in January it expects its second quarter, ending March 30, will see earnings in the range of 35 cents to 45 cents per share, compared with 61 cents per share for the same period last year. In the first quarter, ended Dec. 30, the company earned $ 140.5 million, or $ 1.10 per share. The IIcx, which may eventually make the Mac II obsolete, is just over 12 inches wide, compared with 18 inches for other Mac II computers. It will be available in four configurations: _ With one megabyte of memory and one floppy disk, selling for $ 4,669 _ With one megabyte of internal memory and a 40 megabyte hard disk drive, selling for $ 5,369 _ With four megabytes of memory and an 80 megabyte hard disk, for $ 7,069 _ A similar computer with four megabytes of memory, an 80 megabyte hard disk and A-UX, <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s version of the <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T Unix operating system, for $ 7,552 One of the new high-resolution monitors <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> will show off has a 21-inch, two-page monochrome screen that measures 15 inches horizontally by 11.3 inches vertically. It allows user to display two pages side-by-side along with menus and scroll bars. The monitor carries a suggested retail price of $ 2,149. Its companion video card is priced at $ 599. The new Portrait Display, priced at $ 1,099, has a 15-inch diagonal flat screen that can show an entire page of text and graphics, including menus and scroll bars.
