<TEXT>
 ABOARD DELTA FLIGHT 839 -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Passengers and flight attendants on one <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> flight expressed exasperation today over a potentially time-consuming job action implemented by pilots nationwide in support of strikers at rival <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. The pilots union covering most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers ordered members to take enhanced safety procedures starting today because of safety concerns it said have arisen out of the 4-day-old strike at the troubled Miami-based Eastern. But if the views of people aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> were any indication, that was n't the pilots' only motive. `` I think they are doing it more out of sympathy,'' said passenger <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Licenzi </PERSON>, an engineer from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, after the cockpit crew delayed takeoff for nearly a half an hour on the three-quarter full flight because of what the captain called `` cargo loading.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> flight attendant, who did not wish to be quoted by name, said the same cargo loading delay had waylaid the flight for 20 minutes on an earlier Atlanta-to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> run. The pilots declined to talk with an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter aboard and made no announcement to other passengers regarding the job action. `` It's just going to aggravate people all day long,'' said the flight attendant, a 10-year Delta veteran. `` What's the point of it?'' She said `` I think it's solidarity for their union. It's just they're little way of getting even.'' Passenger <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, a merchant marine ship captain en route to <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>, said of the Eastern strike and the pilots' sympathy action: `` I think it's in poor taste Nobody wins.'' The Eastern strike has been a boon to Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, which in ordinary times is a highly profitable carrier that gets good marks from passengers for service. Thousands of erstwhile <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> passengers have been re-booked on <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> flights since the strike began Saturday. Despite the delay today, at least some passengers appeared not to mind and directed their criticism toward <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which has been reeling from financial losses and chronic complaints about service. `` I hope Eastern goes out of business and <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> can buy their routes,'' said a plastics company sales manager from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> who was aboard the <LOCATION> Miami-Atlanta </LOCATION> flight.
