<HEAD>De Beers 1988 Net Profit Up 101.9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 De <ORGANIZATION> Beers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest diamond producer, said Tuesday its profits doubled last year, but predicted a slowdown in world economic growth would cut into 1989 sales The year-end results showed that net attributable earnings amounted to 2.090 billion rand, or $ 877 million, from 1.035 billion rand a year earlier. De Beers chairman <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogilvie </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said revenue rose strongly, helped by a 13.5 percent price increase in May last year. He said there had been a slight slowdown in sales to the Japanese market towards the end of the year, apparently due to Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s illness at the time. De Beers results follow the announcement earlier this year by the group's marketing arm, the Central Selling Organization, that sales of rough gem and industrial diamonds by the organization totalled $ 4.17 billion in 1988, up 35.7 percent from 1987's total of $ 3.08 billion.
