<SECOND>BC-Scotland-American Investment, Adv 12,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scots Want to Attract More U.S. Investment Before 1992</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Scotland-Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISHOPTON, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s only foreign factory soars above the Scottish countryside outside <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>, a giant glass-metal structure that looks unique. It is n't. The <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> plant is modeled on the company's <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> headquarters. Its parent company is one of 275 American businesses operating in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The Scots historically have been highly successful in attracting foreign businesses, although the pace of overseas investment has slackened in the past few years. They hope the pace will accelerate again ahead of 1992, when the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> is to become one barrier-free marketplace. Investment has meant a great deal to <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s hard-hit economy in the 1980s, creating jobs where the unemployment rate is 10.3 percent. But foreign owners of Scottish factories have been criticized for creating a segment of the economy that thrives on low-skilled assembly jobs. `` For the large companies 1992 will not come as a big surprise. They were already here. What we are talking about here are the small - to medium-sized companies for whom expansion in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> would be the next logical step,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official Many companies are establishing a presence in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, by setting up manufacturing operations or arranging joint ventures and licensing agreements to ensure they're not shut out of the single European market of 320 million consumers when 1992 arrives. The largest share of investment in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> has come from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, much of it in electronics, which has created a `` Silicon <PERSON> Glen </PERSON>.'' It is the largest such concentration in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, stretching from <LOCATION> Prestwick </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Dundee </ORGANIZATION> in the central part of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, where most of the 5.1 million population lives. Investment in 1987-88 totaled $ 580 million and created more than 6,700 jobs, vs. a $ 1.2 billion invesmtment credited with creating nearly 8,200 jobs in 1984-85, government statistics show. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share in the latest year totaled $ 194 million, which created or safeguarded about 3,600 jobs. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> tries to attract companies in electronics and health care, where it already has a substantial infrastructure that gives investors easy access to components and research. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> also sells the experience of existing American companies. `` We're very, very comfortable with the decision that took <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> to establish in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> McGowan </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> manager. He said the company already has expanded operations at the 10-month-old plant. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s promoters also boast that the work force is cheap compared with those of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and other European countries. Moreover, they say Scots are highly educated and readily available because of the high jobless rate. The English language also is a big factor in attracting American investors, experts said. `` It's not just language. It's language and culture. The Americans find the work force very similar to the work force in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said. Nonetheless, many overseas entrepreneurs remain skeptical of doing business here. For one thing, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> is remote, separated from the European continent by water. Critics also contend the Scottish workforce is not as cheap, flexible and well educated as the government officially proclaims. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edinburgh </ORGANIZATION>, said large Japanese companies such as <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> have preferred to establish factories in northeast <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. Another problem is what business executives call a history of union stubbornness in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, for example, abandoned plans to build an electronics plant in <LOCATION> Dundee </LOCATION> last year because of labor opposition to a single union there. `` We certainly have lost a lot of economic opportunity because of union intransigence,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, Scottish director of the Confederation of British Industry. In addition, some critics worry that foreign companies are n't transplanting their decision-making and research work to <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Others say only a narrow range of overseas-based industries are setting up here, leaving the Scots vulnerable if those industries suffer downturns. `` There's been a high mortality rate of plants that came here in the 1960s and 1970s that did n't survive the'80s when the electronics industry slowed down,'' <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
