<DATELINE>MIAMI SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This airport bedroom community, founded by aviation pioneer <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtiss </PERSON>, was hit especially hard when <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> idled 9,500 employees in last two days. <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hidalgo </PERSON> has owned the <LOCATION> Eldorado </LOCATION> jewelry shop for eight years in the corner of the central drug store in this city of 12,000 on the edge of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Now he wonders if he'll be looking for a new job soon. Open for 2 -LCB- hours Tuesday, <PERSON> Hidalgo </PERSON> went to his desk to locate his only receipt for the day _ a $ 2 repair. `` By this time of day, I was usually crowded and people were waiting outside,'' said <PERSON> Hidalgo </PERSON>. `` My survival amount to cover everything is $ 100 a day. Yesterday I made $ 62.'' He feels the strike by the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union against money-losing Eastern is to blame. Shopkeepers around the downtown traffic circle estimate 40 percent to 60 percent of their business comes from the airline industry and a significant segment of that from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, whose headquarters is just outside the city. <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, a newsstand employee at the airport for 17 years, was wondering how much longer the airport concession would keep her shop open in the nearly deserted Eastern terminal. `` I live in the Springs, and practically all the people that live in the Springs work for Eastern,'' she said. At one point, she called the strike by the 8,500-member <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union `` very foolish'' but, no matter what happens, she concluded, `` Nobody's going to win.'' Her employer already has closed stores on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s shuttered boarding ramps and is pushing its workers to take vacations or shift to a four-day work week. `` I've been here 17 years and I make $ 5 an hour. I always say half a loaf is better than nothing,'' she said. `` It's going to be a sad thing down here in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. It's bad.'' Ticket agents and skycaps who on Monday were placed on what <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> calls `` no-work status'' were called in Tuesday morning for a meeting with management. A supervisor told them they could apply for unemployment benefits but could be called back at any time. Their medical insurance expired at midnight Monday, no vacation pay would be considered, and questions about early retirement went unanswered. The `` no-work status'' means `` we hope it's a shorter term, in other words, that we hope we'll be able to call them back to work,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Bobbi </PERSON> <PERSON> Giordano </PERSON>. `` We're hoping that they'll be coming back, so that's where that stands. <PERSON> Iza </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmett </PERSON>, a 24-year Eastern veteran who had been working in international passenger services, hugged co-workers and wiped away tears as she headed to pick up a paycheck. `` We do n't get vacation pay, we do n't get severance pay, we do n't get anything,'' she said `` They're upset, very upset, because they want to know what's happening in the future,'' said ramp service manager <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Brazeau </PERSON>, a 23-year Eastern veteran Skycap Red <PERSON> Bloise </PERSON> resents both <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and President `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> ` Ostrich' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, because he has his head in the ground.'' `` They're giving us this no-work status garbage because this way they do n't have to give us the stuff we've earned,'' the 10-year veteran said as he left for home and his children. `` Now that we're out of a job, we wo n't even get to Disney World. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s chief operating officer, said the workers were laid off, but workers were told they had been placed on `` no-work status,'' eligible for unemployment benefits but without severance pay, vacation pay, medical insurance or answers to questions about early retirement. `` The difference is that we hope it's a shorter term, in other words, that we hope we'll be able to call them back to work,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Bobbi </PERSON> <PERSON> Giordano </PERSON>. `` We're hoping that they'll be coming back, so that's where that stands.'' In <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marilynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoss </PERSON>, whose grandmother worked for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, said she could n't be anything but optimistic. `` I think that's the only attitude you can take is be positive,'' she said while filling orders at a gift shop filled with Easter baskets, colorful balloons and St. Patrick's Day fare. Others were n't so enthusiastic. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, operator of Circle Barber Shop and a real estate agent, recalls airline workers mowing lawns and taking jobs pumping gas in previous strikes.
