<FIRST>r f AM-SuddenAcceleration     03-07 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudden Acceleration,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Confusion Between Pedals Is Likely Cause of Sudden Acceleration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The most likely cause of cases of sudden acceleration involving the <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000 and other cars is drivers stepping on the wrong pedal, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The agency, however, said drivers may not be to blame for confusion between accelerator and brake. The difficulty in selecting the right pedal may be `` aggravated by vehicle design,'' the agency said. A yearlong study of sudden acceleration, conducted by the agency's <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, found that a car can suddenly speed up to full power only if the throttle is opened almost completely to provide oxygen to the engine. Other proposed theories of sudden acceleration, such as problems with the cruise control or electronic idle speed control systems, failed to meet the test of an open throttle while the brakes are applied, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> has conducted more than 100 investigations of unwanted acceleration involving 20 manufacturers since the late 1970s. The agency's investigations of the problem have resulted in 26 recalls and manufacturers have conducted another 75 recalls. A major sudden acceleration case involved the West German-made <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>. In late 1986 the company recalled about 250,000 of its 5000-series automobiles for installation of a `` shift-lock'' device, which prevents the transmission from being put into forward or reverse without the brake pedal being depressed. <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> that the report `` is a breath of fresh air as far as we're concerned.'' `` While the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> chose to use the term ` pedal misapplication,' we feel that it is fundamentally what we've been saying,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. He was skeptical that design factors in the <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> could have contributed to confusion among pedals. `` Our pedals are optimized for braking efficiency, for driver control,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` These cars are designed to be driven on autobahns at 100 mph plus.'' The Center for Auto Safety, a critic of the auto industry, declined comment until it could see a copy of the report. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> rejected the conclusion of a Canadian study and some automakers that sudden acceleration was due to driver error. `` ` Driver error' may imply carelessness or willfulness in failing to operate a car properly,'' <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` ` Pedal misapplication' is more descriptive of what occurs. It could happen to even the most attentive driver who inadvertently selects the wrong pedal and continues to do so unwittingly.'' A report by <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>, issued in January, concluded that sudden acceleration `` occurs as a result of driver error.'' Pedal placement, shape and feel may be factors that lead drivers to press the wrong pedal, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. However, the agency said proposals for any design changes must await further research. Complaints of sudden acceleration are based on instances when cars allegedly go to full power from a standstill or slow speed, usually after the driver has moved the automatic transmission from park into drive or reverse, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency excluded from its definition of sudden acceleration instances of high idle speed or throttle sticking.
</TEXT>
