<TEXT>
 A tax-avoidance consultant who owns a bank on the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Saipan </LOCATION> is under indictment on three counts of tax evasion and three counts of signing a false corporate income tax return. <PERSON> Jimmie </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Straw </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dalton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, faces up to 24 years in jail and fines of up to $ 600,000 if convicted on all counts. He was described in a brochure at a recent symposium as having written more than 200 books, reports and articles on finance, investment and offshore banking. He publishes the Offshore Banking News. The indictment claims he `` substantially understated'' his income on individual and corporate tax returns for 1982, 1983 and 1984. He was indicted Friday. On Monday, he denied evading taxes. `` I've got nothing to hide,'' he said. He said he had been warned in 1985 that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> official had drawn up a `` hit list'' of people involved in banking in <LOCATION> Saipan </LOCATION>. He said his records were subpoenaed in 1986.
