<HEAD>Eastern Interviewing for Flight Attendants as Strike Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3 grafs for 6th graf pvs, The airline's, to update with
Boston interviews and union response and to CORRECT name of union; also
CORRECTS 2nd salary figure in 13th graf to $1,200 instead of $2,000. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even with its planes idled and thousands of its employees on furlough because of a strike, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> was interviewing applicants for jobs as flight attendants Tuesday. Union members, picketing outside the hotel where the interviews were held, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> was trying to line up non-union attendants to replace <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> members. The company denied it and said it was simply going ahead with the interviews because of help-wanted ads it placed before the strike. Several of the 15 to 20 young men and women who showed up for interviews said they were not aware that the airline was in difficulty. Similar interviews were held in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on Sunday and Monday and also were picketed by unionized attendants. <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>, secretary-treasurer of Local 533 of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the flight attendants, said Eastern was also interviewing in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Tuesday and was planning interviews in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Wednesday. `` We are meeting these people at every hotel,'' Ms. <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON> said. `` We have had great success in convincing people to turn away. We handed them a flier and told them about other airlines that were hiring flight attendants and would pay them more money, and we said please come back some day when things are better at Eastern.'' Flight attendants have joined <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots in honoring picket lines thrown up Saturday by the airline's 8,500-member Machinists union. Eastern announced Monday it was sending more than 5,000 workers home. And most planes were grounded by the crippled airline, the nation's seventh largest. This did n't deter a young woman who would identify herself only as <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> as she emerged from the room where she had filled out a form and talked with an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> representative about future employment. `` I want a job,'' she said. `` I really didnt know about the controversy that was going on.'' The airline's ad, which appeared Sunday, said, `` Tired of the nine to five grind? See more of the world in a month than most people see in a lifetime. Eastern is currently recruiting flight attendants and would like to consider you a candidate.'' The ad said the jobs would pay $ 1,000 to $ 1,200 per month in base salary plus expenses. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, who was conducting the interviews, said they were `` basically informational.'' Asked in a telephone interview whether the interviewing session had anything to do with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s current difficulties, <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said, `` Yes, it does. I think at present we need to make sure that we can get this operation back on its feet.'' `` We are not passing out applications,'' he said. `` We are just trying to get an idea of those individuals who would be interested in working for Eastern in the event that we had to do some replacement of flight attendants.'' When a reporter arrived at the hotel, however, <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said, `` What we are doing is trying to fill the commitment we made in the newspaper ads, rather than lock the door. We had no idea we would be faced with this situation.'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said he believed the ads were placed last Wednesday. Outside the hotel, <PERSON> Teal </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, a stewardess with Eastern for five years and a member of the union, said, `` They're hiring scab flight attendants to replace us.'' <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, an official of a union that represents workers at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION> where the interviews took place, said he telephoned <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, general manager of the hotel, Monday night and `` asked him to throw Eastern out of there.'' `` His response was that they had already rented the place, and they could n't legally get out of it,'' said <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, who is executive secretary-treasurer of Local 25 of the Hotel and Restaurant Employees Union. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said of the company, `` It was a situation that they could have avoided. I do n't foresee it happening again.'' The airline has 7,000 flight attendants. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashelford </PERSON>, a picket who said he had been with Eastern for 23 years, suggested new attendants would be hired at much lower pay. He said an experienced flight attendant makes about $ 1,800 a month plus $ 25 an hour for flying time in excess of 75 hours a month. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, told that the pickets did not believe his account of the purpose of the interviews, said, `` They probably would n't, as a result of the climate that we have now at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. But I can assure you there has been no plan made as a result of what has happened.'' The woman named <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> said company interviewers did not talk to her about the union or tell her that people were being laid off. She also said she was not given encouragement that she would get a job. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Folefac </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> said he was aware of the strike, but that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> representatives told him `` they were just trying to honor the ad in the paper.'' He, too, said they did not give him any encouragement.
