<HEAD>House Subcommittee Moves Toward Eastern Strike Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New in first 6 grafs with subcommittee passage of bill; Picks
up 3rd graf pvs bgng: But Bush, ... adding 3 grafs at end with separate
bill to protect ticket holders, vote breakdown. Also moved on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A divided <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel approved a union-sought bill Tuesday that would compel President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to intervene in the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> strike, despite administration insistence that such involvement would not settle the bitter dispute. The legislation, passed 21-12 by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION>, would require <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to appoint an emergency board to study the impasse that has grounded most of the carrier's flights and to recommend a solution. During this process, there would be a cooling-off period of up to 60 days in which the striking employees would return to work. The bill is not expected to reach the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor until sometime next week. Although many lawmakers concede that there are not enough votes in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to override an expected presidential veto, Democrats say the exercise is worthwhile because of the pressure it places on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to find a solution to the work stoppage. `` When we send the bill to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s desk, we're passing a hot potato back to him,'' Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>, D-Ore., said after the panel's vote `` What's his solution?'' The legislation would require the emergency board to study the dispute between not only <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and its striking machinists, but between the airline and two other unions whose contracts have expired: the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, which represents flight attendants. `` We want to stick it all into the same bag, settle it all at once,'' said the subcommittee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberstar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Minn </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Bsh </PERSON>, in a session with White House reporters, repeated his belief that the `` free collective bargaining'' process should resolve the standoff. He said it would be `` inappropriate'' for the government to impose a solution. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> told the panel that he would recommend that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> veto the legislation, arguing that the `` frustrations and animosity'' between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s management and its striking workers was building and would fester despite a board's appointment `` You ca n't run an airline where you have the kind of animosity over a period of time building up,'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said. Democrats, however, argued that a board could produce a solution to the dispute, which began Saturday and has pitted Eastern against its 8,500 machinists and ramp workers represented by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>. Most of the carrier's pilots and flight attendants have also walked off their jobs in support of the machinists, in a dispute focusing on wages and benefits `` The emergency board gives cover to both parties to reach agreement,'' said subcommittee chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberstar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Minn </LOCATION>. Elsewhere, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> also sought to pressure <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to appoint a board, telling reporters that presidential leadership was needed. `` He can do as previous presidents have done, as President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did in the steel crisis,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. `` That's leadership. <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> sounded a similar theme to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee, blaming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s failure to appoint a board for the strike. `` It is time for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to fill the leadership void the president has created,'' <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> told the lawmakers. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> told the subcommittee that administration remains poised to introduce legislation that would prohibit secondary boycotts of railroads and other airlines that labor has threatened to support the Eastern strikers. `` A strike at Eastern alone does not substantially disrupt this nation's transportation system,'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said. `` It is only the specter of secondary activity that threatens to hold hostage this nation's economy and our global competitive position.'' In his session with reporters, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reiterated that secondary boycotts `` are not in the public interest and I will send legislation to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to forbid them, if that is necessary.'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> drew occasionally testy questions from the panel's Democrats, who kept demanding to know why the administration has so far adopted a passive role in the dispute `` There has n't been any rolling up of sleeves and getting in there,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON>, D-Calif. `` I'm not afraid to go anywhere, anyplace, and put anybody in a room'' to find a settlement to the strike, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> responded Even some Republicans were critical of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s owner, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, and said they had not decided whether they would support the Democrats' call for an emergency board. But other <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers supported <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s stance. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammerschmidt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` To convene an emergency board and return to the wages and working conditions of last week will only further bleed <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and endanger its survival.'' Democrats said they expected the administration to have little chance of getting its bill through the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. All 19 Democrats on the subcommittee who voted supported the legislation. All but two of the panel's Republicans opposed the measure: Reps. <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Boehlert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Molinari </PERSON>, both from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. On a related issue, <PERSON> Boehlert </PERSON> introduced a bill Tuesday that would require air carriers to submit plans to protect their ticketholders in case of bankruptcy. <PERSON> Boehlert </PERSON> said `` tens of thousands'' of travelers have already purchased tickets for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flights, some of which might not be redeemed if the airline reorganizes under the bankruptcy laws.
