<HEAD>Lone Star Seeks to Restructure Steel Unit's Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facilities </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Lone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>, is negotiating with lenders to stretch out payments on $ 135 million in bank debt, the parent company said. The steel unit, formerly known as <ORGANIZATION> Lone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, faces a $ 44 million payment on the debt March 31. The holding company is not responsible for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' debt. <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facilities </ORGANIZATION> met Friday with a group of its bank lenders, led by <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, to discuss restructuring the debt, officials said Monday. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Lone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> said auditor <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> may include an `` explanatory paragraph'' in its report on the company's financial results for the year The paragraph, described as slightly less severe than a qualified report, would reflect uncertainties about Lone Star's ability to complete the proposed debt restructuring, the company told the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. Buoyed by overly optimistic projections of demand for its oilfield products, <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> borrowed heavily last year to purchase high-quality slab steel used to manufacture pipe. Bank debt in the year soared to $ 144.1 million from $ 108.3 million. But the steep downturn in world oil prices dried up the market for oilfield products, and Lone Star in 1988 posted a $ 24.8 million loss. Despite two profitable quarters early in the year, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> steel operations contributed more than half of the loss. As a result of the latest downturn, the company in August laid off 300 workers at its steel mill in Lone Star, which in its heyday employed more than 6,000. In January, the company eliminated 150 additional jobs as part of its reorganization of its steel operations. Lone <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> said it has tried without success to find other sources of financing. To raise cash, the company said, it sought possible joint-venture partners or buyers for selected assets.
