<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Up Moderately</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar inched up against the Japanese yen after opening lower in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Wednesday, and share prices also rose on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar, which opened at 128.68 yen, down 0.35 yen from Tuesday's close, inched up to 128.78 yen by late morning. The currency moved in a range between 128.65 yen and 128.90 yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained 61.08 points Tuesday, added another 135.30 points, or 0.42 percent, to finish the morning session at 32,073.24. Dealers said the index rose after investors regained confidence in the market after a favorable showing in Tuesday's session. Stability in the foreign exchange market also contributed to the Nikkei's rise Wednesday, said <PERSON> Yukio </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakajima </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. He added, however, `` There are still some uncertainties over how the stock scandal will affect the government.'' The Nikkei index declined upon the start of trading Tuesday following the arrest of a leading executive on charges of bribery in a major stock-profiteering scandal with links to leading politicians. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kato </PERSON>, former vice labor minister, was arrested on bribery charges in the same stock scandal but morning trading closed before reports of the arrest surfaced. In currency dealings, the dollar slumped from the previous day mainly due to selling for profit-taking, traders said. Market participants were reluctant to make major moves before Friday's release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employment figures for February, said one trader.
